// Edexcel A-Level Mathematics (9MA0) вҖ” Statistics S1вҖ“S8
// Written Question Bank: 15 green + 15 amber + 10 red per topic = 40 per topic, 320 total

const EDEXCEL_WRITTEN_S1_S8 = {

  // в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җ
  // S1: Statistical Sampling
  // в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җ
  'S1': {
    name: 'Statistical Sampling',
    green: [
      { q: 'State the meaning of the term <em>population</em> in statistics.', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'A population is the entire group of individuals or items under investigation. It includes every member that could potentially be studied, not just those selected for a sample.' },
      { q: 'State the meaning of the term <em>sampling frame</em> and give one example.', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'A sampling frame is a complete list of all members of the population from which a sample can be drawn. Example: an electoral register (list of all registered voters in a constituency).' },
      { q: 'Describe how to carry out <strong>simple random sampling</strong> from a population of 200 people when a sample of 20 is required.', marks: 3, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'Step 1: Assign each of the 200 people a unique number from 1 to 200. Step 2: Use a random number generator (or random number tables) to generate 20 distinct numbers between 1 and 200. Step 3: Select the people corresponding to those 20 numbers.' },
      { q: 'Describe how to carry out <strong>systematic sampling</strong> from a population of 300 when a sample of 15 is required.', marks: 3, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'Step 1: Calculate the sampling interval: \\(k = \\frac{300}{15} = 20\\). Step 2: Select a random starting point between 1 and 20 (e.g. 7). Step 3: Select every 20th person after that: 7, 27, 47, 67, вҖҰ up to the 15th selection.' },
      { q: 'A school has 480 students. A stratified sample of 40 students is required. The school has three year groups: Year 10 has 180 students, Year 11 has 160 students, and Year 12 has 140 students. Calculate the number of students to be sampled from Year 10.', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'Number from Year 10 \\(= \\frac{180}{480} \\times 40 = \\frac{180 \\times 40}{480} = \\frac{7200}{480} = 15\\). So 15 students should be sampled from Year 10.' },
      { q: 'State one advantage and one disadvantage of using a <strong>census</strong> rather than a sample.', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'Advantage: A census gives completely accurate information about the whole population вҖ” there is no sampling error. Disadvantage: A census is very time-consuming and expensive, especially for large populations.' },
      { q: 'State one advantage and one disadvantage of <strong>simple random sampling</strong>.', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'Advantage: Every member of the population has an equal chance of being selected, so it is free from bias. Disadvantage: It requires a complete sampling frame, which may not always be available or practical to compile.' },
      { q: 'State one advantage and one disadvantage of <strong>systematic sampling</strong>.', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'Advantage: It is simple and quick to carry out once the sampling interval is calculated. Disadvantage: If there is a periodic pattern in the population list that coincides with the sampling interval, the sample may be biased.' },
      { q: 'A company has 240 employees. A stratified sample of 30 is required. The company has two departments: Production (168 employees) and Administration (72 employees). Calculate the number of employees to sample from Administration.', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'Number from Administration \\(= \\frac{72}{240} \\times 30 = \\frac{72 \\times 30}{240} = \\frac{2160}{240} = 9\\). So 9 employees should be sampled from Administration.' },
      { q: 'State one advantage and one disadvantage of <strong>stratified sampling</strong>.', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'Advantage: It ensures that each subgroup (stratum) is proportionally represented in the sample, giving a more representative sample. Disadvantage: It requires knowledge of which stratum each member belongs to, and a complete sampling frame.' },
      { q: 'Describe <strong>opportunity sampling</strong> and state one disadvantage of this method.', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'Opportunity sampling involves selecting individuals who are conveniently available at the time of the study (e.g. asking people passing by on the street). Disadvantage: The sample is unlikely to be representative of the whole population, as only certain types of people may be available, leading to bias.' },
      { q: 'A researcher wants a sample of 5 from a list of 25 people numbered 1вҖ“25. Using random numbers 14, 07, 31, 22, 03, 19, 08 (ignoring repeats and numbers over 25), write down the sample selected.', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'Take numbers in order, ignoring those over 25: 14 вң“, 07 вң“, 31 вң— (over 25), 22 вң“, 03 вң“, 19 вң“. Sample: {3, 7, 14, 19, 22}.' },
      { q: 'State what is meant by a <strong>statistic</strong> and give one example.', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'A statistic is any quantity calculated from sample data that does not depend on any unknown population parameters. Example: the sample mean \\(\\bar{x}\\) is a statistic calculated from a sample.' },
      { q: 'A factory produces items on four production lines with 60, 90, 120, and 30 items respectively. A stratified sample of 20 items is required. How many items should be selected from the production line with 90 items?', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'Total items = 60 + 90 + 120 + 30 = 300. Number from line with 90: \\(\\frac{90}{300} \\times 20 = \\frac{90 \\times 20}{300} = 6\\). So 6 items should be selected.' },
      { q: 'State the difference between a <strong>parameter</strong> and a <strong>statistic</strong>.', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'A parameter is a numerical property of the whole population (e.g. the population mean \\(\\mu\\)), whereas a statistic is a value calculated from a sample (e.g. the sample mean \\(\\bar{x}\\)). Parameters are usually unknown; statistics are used to estimate them.' },
    ],
    amber: [
      { q: 'A hospital wants to survey patients about their experience. It has 3 wards: Medical (200 patients), Surgical (150 patients), and Paediatric (50 patients). A stratified sample of 40 patients is required. Calculate the number from each ward and describe how the final selection within each ward should be made.', marks: 5, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'Total = 200 + 150 + 50 = 400 patients.\n\nMedical: \\(\\frac{200}{400} \\times 40 = 20\\)\nSurgical: \\(\\frac{150}{400} \\times 40 = 15\\)\nPaediatric: \\(\\frac{50}{400} \\times 40 = 5\\)\n\nCheck: 20 + 15 + 5 = 40 вң“\n\nWithin each ward, number the patients and use a random number generator to select the required number. This ensures each patient within the ward has an equal chance of selection.' },
      { q: 'A researcher interviews shoppers leaving a supermarket on a Tuesday morning. Give two reasons why this sample is likely to be biased.', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'Reason 1: Only people who shop on Tuesday mornings are included. This excludes people who work full-time on weekdays, so the sample is likely to over-represent retired people or those not in full-time employment.\n\nReason 2: Only people who use that particular supermarket are included. This may exclude people in different income groups or locations who shop elsewhere.\n\nBoth reasons mean the sample is unlikely to be representative of the general population.' },
      { q: 'A school uses systematic sampling to select 25 students from a list of 500 students. The random starting number is 12.\n(a) State the sampling interval.\n(b) Write down the first three students selected.', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '(a) Sampling interval \\(k = \\frac{500}{25} = 20\\).\n\n(b) Start at 12, then add 20 each time:\nFirst student: 12\nSecond student: 12 + 20 = 32\nThird student: 32 + 20 = 52\n\nSo the first three students selected are numbers 12, 32, and 52.' },
      { q: 'Compare <strong>stratified sampling</strong> and <strong>quota sampling</strong>. State one similarity and two differences.', marks: 5, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'Similarity: Both methods divide the population into subgroups and take a proportion from each group, ensuring representation of different types within the population.\n\nDifference 1: In stratified sampling, individuals are selected randomly within each stratum; in quota sampling, the researcher chooses individuals non-randomly until the quota for each group is filled.\n\nDifference 2: Stratified sampling requires a complete sampling frame; quota sampling does not require a sampling frame, making it easier and cheaper to carry out.' },
      { q: 'A pharmaceutical company tests a new drug on a sample of 60 patients from a hospital database of 900 patients. The patients are categorised by age group: Under 40 (270 patients), 40вҖ“60 (360 patients), Over 60 (270 patients).\nCalculate the number of patients to include from each age group in a stratified sample.', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'Total = 900 patients, sample size = 60.\n\nUnder 40: \\(\\frac{270}{900} \\times 60 = \\frac{270 \\times 60}{900} = 18\\)\n40вҖ“60: \\(\\frac{360}{900} \\times 60 = \\frac{360 \\times 60}{900} = 24\\)\nOver 60: \\(\\frac{270}{900} \\times 60 = \\frac{270 \\times 60}{900} = 18\\)\n\nCheck: 18 + 24 + 18 = 60 вң“' },
      { q: 'Explain why a sample of internet users obtained by an online poll is unlikely to be a simple random sample of the general public.', marks: 3, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'An online poll only reaches people who have internet access and who choose to participate. This excludes elderly people, those without internet access, and those who are not interested in the topic. Furthermore, responses are self-selecting вҖ” people with strong opinions are more likely to respond. This makes the sample biased and not representative of the general public, so it cannot be a simple random sample.' },
      { q: 'A council wants to survey residents about a new road scheme. It considers two methods:\nMethod A: Send a questionnaire to every 50th house on the electoral register.\nMethod B: Stand in the town centre on a Saturday and interview passers-by.\nCompare these two methods, stating which is more appropriate and why.', marks: 5, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'Method A is systematic sampling; Method B is opportunity sampling.\n\nMethod A is more appropriate. It uses the electoral register as a sampling frame, so every registered household has a chance of being selected. The sampling is random (systematic with a random start), so results are more representative of residents.\n\nMethod B is biased: only people who visit the town centre on a Saturday are surveyed. This excludes residents who are elderly, disabled, or at work, and over-represents people who shop in town, so results would not represent all residents.\n\nConclusion: Method A is more appropriate as it is more representative and less subject to bias.' },
      { q: 'A survey of 50 people is conducted to find out about reading habits. The researcher surveys the first 50 people to arrive at a library on Monday morning.\n(a) State the sampling method used.\n(b) Give two reasons why this sample may not represent the reading habits of the general population.', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '(a) Opportunity (convenience) sampling.\n\n(b) Reason 1: Library visitors are more likely to read than the general population, so their reading habits will not be typical.\n\nReason 2: People who visit a library on Monday morning are likely to be retired or not in full-time work, so the sample will not represent working-age adults.' },
      { q: 'A company employs 500 people across three regions: North (200), Midlands (175), South (125). A stratified sample of 40 employees is taken.\n(a) How many employees should be sampled from the Midlands?\n(b) Describe how you would use a random number table to select the Midlands sample.', marks: 5, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '(a) Midlands: \\(\\frac{175}{500} \\times 40 = \\frac{175 \\times 40}{500} = \\frac{7000}{500} = 14\\). So 14 employees from the Midlands.\n\n(b) Number the 175 Midlands employees from 001 to 175. Read three-digit groups from the random number table. Accept any number from 001вҖ“175 and reject numbers 176вҖ“999 and 000. Continue until 14 distinct numbers have been selected. Select the employees corresponding to these numbers.' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by <strong>sampling bias</strong> and describe one scenario in which systematic sampling could produce a biased sample.', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'Sampling bias occurs when the method of sampling means that some members of the population are more likely to be selected than others, so the sample is not representative of the population.\n\nSystematic sampling could produce a biased sample if the list of the population has a periodic pattern that coincides with the sampling interval. For example, if a list of houses alternates between detached and semi-detached, and the sampling interval is 2, then only one type of house would be selected, giving a biased sample.' },
      { q: 'A school has students in Year 12 and Year 13. Year 12 has 180 students and Year 13 has 120 students. A stratified random sample of 25 students is required.\n(a) Calculate the number of Year 12 and Year 13 students to include.\n(b) State one reason why stratified sampling is more appropriate than simple random sampling here.', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '(a) Total = 180 + 120 = 300.\n\nYear 12: \\(\\frac{180}{300} \\times 25 = 15\\)\nYear 13: \\(\\frac{120}{300} \\times 25 = 10\\)\n\nCheck: 15 + 10 = 25 вң“\n\n(b) Stratified sampling ensures Year 12 and Year 13 students are proportionally represented. A simple random sample might, by chance, include too many or too few from one year group.' },
      { q: 'Define a <strong>simple random sample</strong> and state two conditions that must be satisfied for a sampling method to be considered simple random.', marks: 3, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'A simple random sample is a sample of size \\(n\\) taken from a population of size \\(N\\) such that every possible sample of size \\(n\\) has an equal probability of being chosen.\n\nCondition 1: Every individual in the population must have an equal probability of being selected.\nCondition 2: The selection of each individual must be independent of the selection of all others.' },
      { q: 'A researcher investigating TV viewing habits asks students in a common room to fill in a questionnaire. Give two ways in which this sampling method could introduce bias.', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'Bias 1: Only students who happen to be in the common room at that time are surveyed. Students who are in lessons or at sports practice are excluded, so the sample is not representative of all students.\n\nBias 2: Students who are willing to fill in the questionnaire may differ from those who refuse. Those who watch more TV may be more (or less) willing to respond, leading to non-response or self-selection bias.' },
      { q: 'A factory produces items on a production line that runs 24 hours a day. Quality control requires a sample of 48 items per day. Describe how systematic sampling could be used to select the sample, and state one potential problem with this approach.', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'Method: There are 24 hours Г— 60 minutes = 1440 minutes per day. Sampling interval \\(k = \\frac{1440}{48} = 30\\) minutes. Choose a random start between 0 and 30 minutes past midnight, then sample one item every 30 minutes throughout the day.\n\nPotential problem: If the production line has a periodic fault or calibration issue that occurs every 30 minutes (e.g. a machine recalibrates every 30 minutes), then only faulty or only good items at that cycle point would be sampled, introducing bias.' },
      { q: 'A research organisation surveys households about energy use. It decides to sample 1 in every 20 households from the council tax register.\n(a) State the sampling method used.\n(b) Explain how the random start should be chosen.\n(c) State one advantage of this method over simple random sampling for this context.', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '(a) Systematic sampling.\n\n(b) Choose a random integer between 1 and 20 inclusive (e.g. using a random number generator or random number tables). This is the first household selected.\n\n(c) Systematic sampling is simpler and quicker to carry out than simple random sampling when the population is large, as you only need to identify one random starting point rather than generating a large set of random numbers.' },
    ],
    red: [
      { q: 'A local authority wants to find out residents\' opinions on a proposed new leisure centre. It plans to post questionnaires to 500 households chosen randomly from the council tax register.\n(a) Identify the sampling method being used.\n(b) State two potential sources of bias in this survey.\n(c) Suggest two improvements to the sampling strategy.', marks: 7, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: '(a) Simple random sampling (households selected randomly from the council tax register as a sampling frame).\n\n(b) Source 1: Non-response bias вҖ” not all households will return the questionnaire. Those who respond may have stronger opinions (for or against), making the sample self-selecting.\n\nSource 2: Coverage bias вҖ” the council tax register may not include all residents (e.g. those in temporary accommodation, students in halls of residence).\n\n(c) Improvement 1: Follow up non-respondents with a reminder or phone call to increase response rate and reduce non-response bias.\n\nImprovement 2: Use stratified sampling by ward or by household type (e.g. families, single occupants, elderly) to ensure all sections of the community are proportionally represented.' },
      { q: 'A university wants to investigate the study habits of its 12,000 students. It decides to use a sample of 120 students. The university has faculties: Arts (3000), Science (4800), Engineering (2400), Social Science (1800).\n(a) Explain why stratified sampling is more appropriate than simple random sampling for this investigation.\n(b) Calculate the sample size from each faculty.\n(c) Describe how simple random sampling should be used within each faculty.', marks: 8, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: '(a) Stratified sampling is more appropriate because the faculties differ substantially in size and students in different faculties may have very different study habits. Stratified sampling ensures that each faculty is proportionally represented, giving a more representative sample than simple random sampling, which might by chance under- or over-represent a faculty.\n\n(b) Total = 12000, sample = 120.\nArts: \\(\\frac{3000}{12000} \\times 120 = 30\\)\nScience: \\(\\frac{4800}{12000} \\times 120 = 48\\)\nEngineering: \\(\\frac{2400}{12000} \\times 120 = 24\\)\nSocial Science: \\(\\frac{1800}{12000} \\times 120 = 18\\)\nCheck: 30 + 48 + 24 + 18 = 120 вң“\n\n(c) Within each faculty, number all students from 1 to the faculty size. Use a random number generator to produce the required number of distinct values in the appropriate range. Select the students with those numbers.' },
      { q: 'A medical researcher investigates the effectiveness of a new treatment by studying patients at one hospital over a six-month period. All 80 patients treated with the new drug during this period are included in the study.\n(a) Identify the sampling method and explain whether this constitutes a census or a sample.\n(b) Give two limitations of this approach when drawing conclusions about the treatment\'s effectiveness for the general population.\n(c) Suggest a more rigorous sampling strategy and justify your answer.', marks: 8, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: '(a) This is opportunity sampling вҖ” the researcher takes all available patients from one location over a fixed time. It is a sample (not a census) because it only includes patients at one hospital and over one time period, not all patients in the population who might receive the treatment.\n\n(b) Limitation 1: Patients at one hospital may not be representative of all patients nationally. The hospital may have a particular demographic (e.g. urban, higher income area) so results may not generalise.\n\nLimitation 2: The six-month window may not be representative of all time periods. Seasonal factors (e.g. winter illnesses affecting recovery) could bias results.\n\n(c) A stratified random sample from multiple hospitals across different regions would be more rigorous. Stratify by age group, gender, and severity of condition to ensure all patient types are proportionally represented. Use simple random sampling within each stratum. This would give a more representative sample and allow more valid generalisations about the wider population.' },
      { q: 'Critique the following sampling strategy and suggest improvements:\n"A researcher investigating attitudes to social media among teenagers posts a survey link on a popular social media platform and uses the first 200 responses received."', marks: 7, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: 'Critique:\n\nFlaw 1 (Self-selection bias): Only teenagers who see the post and choose to respond are included. Those with strong views about social media are more likely to respond, meaning the sample does not represent all teenagers.\n\nFlaw 2 (Platform bias): Only teenagers who use that particular platform are reached. Teenagers who do not use social media (or who use a different platform) are excluded, which is ironic given the study topic.\n\nFlaw 3 (No sampling frame): Taking the first 200 responses is not random вҖ” early responders may be more active social media users, introducing further bias.\n\nFlaw 4 (No stratification): There is no control over the age, gender, or demographic mix of respondents.\n\nImprovements:\n1. Use stratified random sampling from school registers, stratifying by age and gender.\n2. Conduct the survey in schools to reach teenagers who may not use social media.\n3. Follow up non-respondents to reduce non-response bias.' },
      { q: 'A polling company wants to predict the outcome of a local election. It surveys 400 people from a town of 20,000 registered voters.\n(a) Describe a stratified sampling strategy the company could use, stating at least two stratification variables.\n(b) Explain two reasons why even a well-designed sample of 400 might not accurately predict the election result.', marks: 7, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: '(a) Stratification variables could include: age group (18вҖ“34, 35вҖ“54, 55+), ward/area of town, and past voting behaviour (if available).\n\nStrategy: Obtain the electoral register and divide voters into strata by age group and ward. Calculate the proportion from each stratum and multiply by 400 to find the sample size for each group. Within each stratum, use simple random sampling (assign numbers and use a random number generator) to select respondents. This ensures all age groups and areas are proportionally represented.\n\n(b) Reason 1: Non-response bias вҖ” not everyone asked will agree to be surveyed. Those who refuse may have different voting intentions, so the achieved sample may not represent all voters.\n\nReason 2: Social desirability bias / late swing вҖ” respondents may not reveal their true voting intention (e.g. unwilling to admit voting for an unpopular party), or voters may change their mind between the survey and election day, making predictions inaccurate.' },
      { q: 'A manufacturer tests the lifetime of light bulbs. It tests a sample of 50 bulbs from a batch of 5000. The bulbs are destroyed during testing.\n(a) Explain why a census would be inappropriate here.\n(b) Suggest and justify an appropriate sampling method.\n(c) The batch contains bulbs from 4 different machines (1250 each). Explain how stratified sampling could be applied.', marks: 7, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: '(a) A census would be inappropriate because testing destroys the bulbs. If every bulb were tested, there would be no bulbs left to sell. Also, testing 5000 bulbs would be extremely time-consuming and expensive.\n\n(b) Stratified sampling (by machine) or systematic sampling would be appropriate.\n\nJustification for systematic: Assign numbers 1вҖ“5000 to the bulbs. Sampling interval \\(k = \\frac{5000}{50} = 100\\). Choose a random start between 1 and 100, then select every 100th bulb. This is quick and ensures bulbs from throughout the production run are included.\n\n(c) With stratified sampling: each machine produces 1250 bulbs, so sample \\(\\frac{1250}{5000} \\times 50 = 12.5\\) вүҲ 13 or 12 bulbs from each machine (adjust rounding to total 50). Within each machine\'s output, use simple random sampling. This ensures any differences between machines are captured in the sample.' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between <strong>random sampling</strong> and <strong>non-random sampling</strong>. For each of the following, state whether it is random or non-random and justify your answer:\n(a) Stratified sampling\n(b) Quota sampling\n(c) Opportunity sampling', marks: 7, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: 'Random sampling: Every member of the population has a known (and non-zero) probability of being selected. The selection is made using a random mechanism.\n\nNon-random sampling: Selection is based on convenience or researcher judgement; not all members have a calculable probability of selection.\n\n(a) Stratified sampling вҖ” Random. The population is divided into strata, but within each stratum, individuals are selected using a random mechanism (e.g. simple random sampling). Each member has a calculable probability of selection.\n\n(b) Quota sampling вҖ” Non-random. Although proportional representation is sought (similar to stratified), the researcher selects individuals within each quota using their own judgement or convenience. There is no random mechanism, so probabilities of selection are not equal or calculable.\n\n(c) Opportunity sampling вҖ” Non-random. Individuals are selected purely on the basis of availability and convenience. There is no random mechanism and no sampling frame, so there is no way to calculate the probability of any individual being selected.' },
      { q: 'A researcher is conducting a study on the dietary habits of adults in the UK. The adult population is approximately 53 million. Discuss the practical and statistical considerations that should influence the choice of sampling method, and recommend a specific method with justification.', marks: 8, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: 'Practical considerations:\n- A census of 53 million adults would be impossibly expensive and time-consuming.\n- No complete sampling frame of all UK adults exists; the closest available is the electoral register, but this excludes non-registered adults.\n- Dietary habits may vary substantially by age, gender, region, and socio-economic group.\n\nStatistical considerations:\n- The sample must be representative of the diverse adult population.\n- Subgroup differences (e.g. age, region) should be captured so that estimates apply to all adults.\n- A random method is needed to avoid bias and to allow valid statistical inference.\n\nRecommendation: Stratified random sampling, stratifying by age group, gender, and region (e.g. North, Midlands, South, Scotland, Wales, Northern Ireland).\n\nJustification: This ensures proportional representation of each demographic group. Within each stratum, simple random sampling removes bias. The method is practical because strata can be defined using census data and the National Health Service register as an approximate sampling frame. This gives a more representative and statistically valid sample than either simple random sampling (which might by chance under-represent a group) or non-random methods (which introduce bias).' },
      { q: 'A survey finds that 62% of respondents support a new bypass road. The survey used opportunity sampling of 150 people at a service station on the bypass route.\n(a) Give three reasons why this figure may not be reliable as an estimate of the proportion of the local population who support the bypass.\n(b) Describe a better method of conducting this survey.', marks: 7, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: '(a) Reason 1: Opportunity sampling at a service station on the bypass route will over-represent people who already use that road. These people are more likely to support the bypass (since they benefit from it), so the 62% will be an overestimate.\n\nReason 2: Only people visiting the service station on that particular day are surveyed. People who live near the proposed bypass but never use the service station are excluded.\n\nReason 3: Self-selection bias вҖ” people who feel strongly about the issue may be more likely to stop and participate, so the sample does not represent those with moderate views or no strong opinion.\n\n(b) Better method: Use stratified random sampling from the local electoral register, stratifying by area (e.g. distance from the proposed route) and age group. Assign numbers to all residents in each stratum and use a random number generator to select respondents. Contact selected individuals by post or telephone to request participation, and follow up non-respondents. This avoids location bias and gives all residents an equal chance of being included.' },
      { q: 'A teacher claims: "I tested a random sample of my students and found the average score was 68%. Therefore, the average score for all students taking this exam nationally is approximately 68%."\nIdentify and explain three flaws in this reasoning.', marks: 7, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: 'Flaw 1 (Scope of inference): The teacher\'s students are not a random sample of all national students вҖ” they form a cluster sample from one class or school. Students at one school may have had better or worse teaching, resources, or ability profile than the national average, so it is invalid to generalise to all national students.\n\nFlaw 2 (Sample size): No information is given about how many students were tested. If only a small number (e.g. 10) were tested, the sample mean will have high variability and is an unreliable estimate of the national mean.\n\nFlaw 3 (Definition of "random"): The teacher says "random sample" but does not describe how the sample was selected. If students were self-selected (e.g. volunteered) or selected by the teacher, the sample is not truly random and may be biased (e.g. higher-ability students selected to demonstrate good performance).' },
    ],
  },

  // в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җ
  // S2: Data Presentation and Measures
  // в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җ
  'S2': {
    name: 'Data Presentation and Measures',
    green: [
      { q: 'The following data shows the ages of 10 employees: 23, 25, 28, 31, 31, 35, 38, 42, 45, 52. Calculate the mean and median age.', marks: 3, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'Mean: \\(\\bar{x} = \\frac{23+25+28+31+31+35+38+42+45+52}{10} = \\frac{350}{10} = 35\\).\n\nMedian: With 10 values, the median is the mean of the 5th and 6th values. Sorted: 23, 25, 28, 31, 31, 35, 38, 42, 45, 52. Median \\(= \\frac{31+35}{2} = 33\\).' },
      { q: 'Given: \\(Q_1 = 14\\), \\(Q_2 = 22\\), \\(Q_3 = 31\\). Calculate the interquartile range (IQR).', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: '\\(\\text{IQR} = Q_3 - Q_1 = 31 - 14 = 17\\).' },
      { q: 'The ages of 5 people are: 18, 22, 25, 30, 35. Calculate the variance and standard deviation.', marks: 4, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'Mean: \\(\\bar{x} = \\frac{18+22+25+30+35}{5} = \\frac{130}{5} = 26\\).\n\nVariance: \\(\\sigma^2 = \\frac{(18-26)^2+(22-26)^2+(25-26)^2+(30-26)^2+(35-26)^2}{5}\\)\n\\(= \\frac{64+16+1+16+81}{5} = \\frac{178}{5} = 35.6\\)\n\nStandard deviation: \\(\\sigma = \\sqrt{35.6} \\approx 5.97\\).' },
      { q: 'The frequency table shows scores in a test:\n| Score | Frequency |\n|-------|-----------|\n| 10 | 3 |\n| 20 | 5 |\n| 30 | 7 |\n| 40 | 4 |\n| 50 | 1 |\nCalculate the mean score.', marks: 3, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: '\\(\\bar{x} = \\frac{\\sum fx}{\\sum f} = \\frac{(10)(3)+(20)(5)+(30)(7)+(40)(4)+(50)(1)}{3+5+7+4+1}\\)\n\\(= \\frac{30+100+210+160+50}{20} = \\frac{550}{20} = 27.5\\)' },
      { q: 'A data set has \\(\\sum x = 180\\) and \\(n = 12\\). Calculate the mean.', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: '\\(\\bar{x} = \\frac{\\sum x}{n} = \\frac{180}{12} = 15\\).' },
      { q: 'The following data set has been arranged in ascending order: 3, 5, 7, 8, 9, 12, 14, 16, 18, 20, 21, 24.\nFind \\(Q_1\\), \\(Q_2\\), and \\(Q_3\\).', marks: 3, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'n = 12.\n\n\\(Q_2\\): mean of 6th and 7th values \\(= \\frac{12+14}{2} = 13\\).\n\n\\(Q_1\\): median of lower half (first 6 values: 3,5,7,8,9,12) \\(= \\frac{7+8}{2} = 7.5\\).\n\n\\(Q_3\\): median of upper half (last 6 values: 14,16,18,20,21,24) \\(= \\frac{18+20}{2} = 19\\).' },
      { q: 'A data set has \\(n=8\\), \\(\\sum x = 96\\), \\(\\sum x^2 = 1216\\). Calculate the standard deviation.', marks: 3, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'Mean: \\(\\bar{x} = \\frac{96}{8} = 12\\).\n\nVariance: \\(\\sigma^2 = \\frac{\\sum x^2}{n} - \\bar{x}^2 = \\frac{1216}{8} - 12^2 = 152 - 144 = 8\\).\n\nStandard deviation: \\(\\sigma = \\sqrt{8} = 2\\sqrt{2} \\approx 2.83\\).' },
      { q: 'Describe the shape of a distribution that is <strong>positively skewed</strong>. State the relationship between mean, median, and mode for this distribution.', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'A positively skewed distribution has a longer tail to the right. The mode is the lowest average, the median is in the middle, and the mean is the highest, pulled up by the extreme values in the right tail. So: mode < median < mean.' },
      { q: 'Calculate the range and interquartile range from the following five-number summary: minimum = 5, \\(Q_1 = 12\\), median = 18, \\(Q_3 = 27\\), maximum = 40.', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'Range = maximum вҲ’ minimum = 40 вҲ’ 5 = 35.\n\nIQR = \\(Q_3 - Q_1 = 27 - 12 = 15\\).' },
      { q: 'A data set has mean 24 and standard deviation 6. A new data set is created by adding 5 to every value. State the new mean and standard deviation.', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'Adding a constant to every value increases the mean by that constant but does not change the spread.\n\nNew mean = 24 + 5 = 29.\nNew standard deviation = 6 (unchanged).' },
      { q: 'A data set has mean 30 and standard deviation 4. A new data set is formed by multiplying every value by 3. State the new mean and standard deviation.', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'Multiplying every value by a constant multiplies both the mean and standard deviation by that constant.\n\nNew mean = 30 Г— 3 = 90.\nNew standard deviation = 4 Г— 3 = 12.' },
      { q: 'Using the formula for outliers, determine whether the value 52 is an outlier given: \\(Q_1 = 20\\), \\(Q_3 = 36\\).', marks: 3, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'IQR = 36 вҲ’ 20 = 16.\n\nUpper fence = \\(Q_3 + 1.5 \\times \\text{IQR} = 36 + 1.5 \\times 16 = 36 + 24 = 60\\).\nLower fence = \\(Q_1 - 1.5 \\times \\text{IQR} = 20 - 24 = -4\\).\n\nSince 52 < 60, the value 52 is NOT an outlier.' },
      { q: 'The heights of 6 plants (cm) are: 12, 15, 15, 18, 20, 26. Find the mean and range.', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'Mean: \\(\\bar{x} = \\frac{12+15+15+18+20+26}{6} = \\frac{106}{6} \\approx 17.7\\) cm.\n\nRange = 26 вҲ’ 12 = 14 cm.' },
      { q: 'A class of 20 students scored the following marks out of 10: the median was 7, \\(Q_1 = 5\\), \\(Q_3 = 9\\). State the interquartile range and explain what it tells us about the data.', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'IQR = \\(Q_3 - Q_1 = 9 - 5 = 4\\).\n\nThe IQR tells us that the middle 50% of students scored within a 4-mark range (between 5 and 9). It measures the spread of the central half of the data and is not affected by extreme values.' },
      { q: 'The times (minutes) taken by 7 students to complete a puzzle are: 8, 10, 10, 12, 14, 15, 22. Calculate the mean and median. Which measure is more appropriate here and why?', marks: 3, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'Mean: \\(\\bar{x} = \\frac{8+10+10+12+14+15+22}{7} = \\frac{91}{7} = 13\\) minutes.\n\nMedian: 4th value (of 7) = 12 minutes.\n\nThe median is more appropriate here because the value 22 is much larger than the others (a potential outlier). The mean is pulled up by this extreme value, so the median gives a better representation of the typical time.' },
    ],
    amber: [
      { q: 'The data below shows weekly wages (ВЈ) for 8 employees, coded as \\(y = \\frac{x - 400}{10}\\):\n\\(y\\): 2, 5, 3, 8, вҲ’1, 4, 6, 1\n\nFind the mean and standard deviation of the original wages \\(x\\).', marks: 5, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'Mean of \\(y\\): \\(\\bar{y} = \\frac{2+5+3+8+(-1)+4+6+1}{8} = \\frac{28}{8} = 3.5\\).\n\nMean of \\(x\\): Since \\(y = \\frac{x-400}{10}\\), we have \\(x = 10y + 400\\).\n\\(\\bar{x} = 10(3.5) + 400 = 35 + 400 = ВЈ435\\).\n\n\\(\\sum y^2 = 4+25+9+64+1+16+36+1 = 156\\)\n\nVariance of \\(y\\): \\(\\sigma_y^2 = \\frac{156}{8} - 3.5^2 = 19.5 - 12.25 = 7.25\\)\n\\(\\sigma_y = \\sqrt{7.25} \\approx 2.693\\)\n\nStandard deviation of \\(x\\): \\(\\sigma_x = 10 \\times \\sigma_y = 10\\sqrt{7.25} \\approx ВЈ26.93\\).' },
      { q: 'Two classes took the same test. Class A: mean = 58, standard deviation = 12. Class B: mean = 65, standard deviation = 5. Compare the performance of the two classes.', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'Class B has a higher mean (65 > 58), so on average Class B performed better.\n\nClass A has a larger standard deviation (12 > 5), meaning Class A\'s scores are more spread out вҖ” there is more variation in performance.\n\nClass B\'s smaller standard deviation indicates their scores are more consistent and clustered close to the mean.\n\nOverall, Class B performed better on average and more consistently than Class A.' },
      { q: 'A histogram has the following information:\n| Class | Frequency density |\n|----------|-------------------|\n| 10 вүӨ x < 20 | 1.5 |\n| 20 вүӨ x < 30 | 3.0 |\n| 30 вүӨ x < 40 | 4.5 |\n| 40 вүӨ x < 60 | 1.0 |\n\nCalculate the frequency for each class and hence the total number of data values.', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'Frequency = frequency density Г— class width.\n\n10 вүӨ x < 20: width = 10, freq = 1.5 Г— 10 = 15\n20 вүӨ x < 30: width = 10, freq = 3.0 Г— 10 = 30\n30 вүӨ x < 40: width = 10, freq = 4.5 Г— 10 = 45\n40 вүӨ x < 60: width = 20, freq = 1.0 Г— 20 = 20\n\nTotal = 15 + 30 + 45 + 20 = 110.' },
      { q: 'A data set has \\(Q_1 = 18\\), \\(Q_3 = 34\\). A value of 58 appears in the data set. Determine whether 58 is an outlier and explain what you would do with it.', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'IQR = \\(Q_3 - Q_1 = 34 - 18 = 16\\).\n\nUpper outlier fence = \\(Q_3 + 1.5 \\times \\text{IQR} = 34 + 1.5(16) = 34 + 24 = 58\\).\n\nSince 58 = 58 (equal to the upper fence), whether 58 is classified as an outlier depends on convention. Using the strict inequality (> 58), it is not an outlier. Using вүҘ 58, it is.\n\nIn practice, I would investigate whether 58 is a genuine extreme value or a recording error. If it is genuine data, it should be kept but noted; if it appears to be an error, it could be removed and the source data checked.' },
      { q: 'Construct a box plot from the following five-number summary: minimum = 4, \\(Q_1 = 11\\), median = 17, \\(Q_3 = 25\\), maximum = 38. Mark any outliers if present, given that the data set also contains the value 44.', marks: 5, tier: 'amber', diagram: true, modelAnswer: 'IQR = 25 вҲ’ 11 = 14.\nUpper fence = 25 + 1.5(14) = 25 + 21 = 46.\nLower fence = 11 вҲ’ 1.5(14) = 11 вҲ’ 21 = вҲ’10.\n\nThe value 44 < 46, so 44 is NOT an outlier.\nThe maximum of 38 is the largest non-outlier value.\n\nBox plot: draw a number line. Box from \\(Q_1 = 11\\) to \\(Q_3 = 25\\) with median line at 17. Whiskers extend from 4 (minimum) to 38 (maximum). The value 44 is within fences so is included as the upper whisker end (replace maximum with 44, since it\'s the actual maximum and not an outlier).\n\nNote: since no value exceeds 46, all values including 44 are included in the whisker. No separate outlier point is plotted.' },
      { q: 'Data on reaction times (seconds) is summarised as: \\(n = 50\\), \\(\\sum x = 87.5\\), \\(\\sum x^2 = 163.5\\).\n(a) Calculate the mean reaction time.\n(b) Calculate the standard deviation.\n(c) A second group of 30 people has mean 1.9 s and standard deviation 0.3 s. Compare the two groups.', marks: 6, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '(a) \\(\\bar{x} = \\frac{87.5}{50} = 1.75\\) s.\n\n(b) \\(\\sigma^2 = \\frac{\\sum x^2}{n} - \\bar{x}^2 = \\frac{163.5}{50} - 1.75^2 = 3.27 - 3.0625 = 0.2075\\)\n\\(\\sigma = \\sqrt{0.2075} \\approx 0.455\\) s.\n\n(c) The first group has a lower mean reaction time (1.75 s vs 1.9 s), suggesting they respond faster on average. The first group also has a slightly larger standard deviation (0.455 s vs 0.3 s), meaning their reaction times are more variable. The second group is slower on average but more consistent.' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by <strong>frequency density</strong> and why it is used on the vertical axis of a histogram rather than frequency.', marks: 3, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'Frequency density = frequency Г· class width.\n\nFrequency density is used on the vertical axis because in a histogram, the area of each bar represents the frequency (or relative frequency) of that class. If bars have different widths (unequal class intervals), using frequency on the vertical axis would make wider bars appear visually larger even if they contain fewer data points. Using frequency density ensures that the area of each bar correctly represents the proportion of the data in that class.' },
      { q: 'The following grouped frequency table shows the time (minutes) spent exercising per week by 60 adults:\n| Time (min) | Frequency |\n|------------|-----------|\n| 0 вүӨ t < 30 | 8 |\n| 30 вүӨ t < 60 | 14 |\n| 60 вүӨ t < 90 | 22 |\n| 90 вүӨ t < 120 | 12 |\n| 120 вүӨ t < 180 | 4 |\n\nCalculate an estimate of the mean time spent exercising.', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'Use midpoints: 15, 45, 75, 105, 150.\n\n\\(\\bar{x} = \\frac{\\sum fm}{\\sum f} = \\frac{(15)(8)+(45)(14)+(75)(22)+(105)(12)+(150)(4)}{60}\\)\n\\(= \\frac{120+630+1650+1260+600}{60} = \\frac{4260}{60} = 71\\) minutes.' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between <strong>variance</strong> and <strong>standard deviation</strong> and state an advantage of using the standard deviation as a measure of spread.', marks: 3, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'Variance (\\(\\sigma^2\\)) is the mean squared deviation from the mean: \\(\\sigma^2 = \\frac{\\sum(x_i - \\bar{x})^2}{n}\\). It is in squared units.\n\nStandard deviation (\\(\\sigma\\)) is the positive square root of the variance: \\(\\sigma = \\sqrt{\\sigma^2}\\). It is in the same units as the original data.\n\nAdvantage of standard deviation: Because it has the same units as the data, it is easier to interpret and compare directly with the mean. For example, if data is in cm, the standard deviation is also in cm.' },
      { q: 'The ages of employees in two companies are summarised below. Company A: mean = 34, SD = 8, n = 40. Company B: mean = 41, SD = 6, n = 60. Calculate the combined mean age of employees from both companies.', marks: 3, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'Total sum for Company A: \\(34 \\times 40 = 1360\\).\nTotal sum for Company B: \\(41 \\times 60 = 2460\\).\n\nCombined mean \\(= \\frac{1360 + 2460}{40 + 60} = \\frac{3820}{100} = 38.2\\) years.' },
      { q: 'A data set contains values: 5, 8, 10, 12, 14, 17, 19, 22, 25, 36. An outlier rule states that a value is an outlier if it is more than 2 standard deviations from the mean. Determine whether 36 is an outlier.', marks: 5, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'Mean: \\(\\bar{x} = \\frac{5+8+10+12+14+17+19+22+25+36}{10} = \\frac{168}{10} = 16.8\\).\n\n\\(\\sum x^2 = 25+64+100+144+196+289+361+484+625+1296 = 3584\\)\n\nVariance: \\(\\sigma^2 = \\frac{3584}{10} - 16.8^2 = 358.4 - 282.24 = 76.16\\)\n\\(\\sigma = \\sqrt{76.16} \\approx 8.727\\)\n\n2 standard deviations above mean = 16.8 + 2(8.727) = 16.8 + 17.45 = 34.25.\n\nSince 36 > 34.25, the value 36 IS an outlier by this rule.' },
      { q: 'The coded data \\(y = x - 50\\) gives \\(\\sum y = 120\\) and \\(\\sum y^2 = 2150\\) for \\(n = 20\\) values. Find the mean and variance of \\(x\\).', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'Mean of \\(y\\): \\(\\bar{y} = \\frac{120}{20} = 6\\).\n\nMean of \\(x\\): \\(\\bar{x} = \\bar{y} + 50 = 56\\).\n\nVariance of \\(y\\): \\(\\sigma_y^2 = \\frac{\\sum y^2}{n} - \\bar{y}^2 = \\frac{2150}{20} - 36 = 107.5 - 36 = 71.5\\).\n\nVariance of \\(x\\): Since \\(y = x - 50\\) is a translation only, \\(\\sigma_x^2 = \\sigma_y^2 = 71.5\\).' },
      { q: 'A box plot shows: minimum = 10, \\(Q_1 = 18\\), median = 25, \\(Q_3 = 33\\), maximum = 41. Describe the distribution in terms of skewness and symmetry, with justification.', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'Check symmetry:\n- \\(Q_2 - Q_1 = 25 - 18 = 7\\)\n- \\(Q_3 - Q_2 = 33 - 25 = 8\\)\n\nThese are approximately equal, suggesting the box is roughly symmetric.\n\n- Lower whisker length: 18 вҲ’ 10 = 8\n- Upper whisker length: 41 вҲ’ 33 = 8\n\nThe whiskers are equal in length.\n\nConclusion: The distribution is approximately symmetric with no significant skew.' },
      { q: 'The weights (kg) of a sample of 6 bags are: 1.2, 1.5, 1.8, 2.1, 2.4, 2.7. Calculate \\(\\sum x\\), \\(\\sum x^2\\), the mean, and variance.', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '\\(\\sum x = 1.2+1.5+1.8+2.1+2.4+2.7 = 11.7\\)\n\n\\(\\sum x^2 = 1.44+2.25+3.24+4.41+5.76+7.29 = 24.39\\)\n\nMean: \\(\\bar{x} = \\frac{11.7}{6} = 1.95\\) kg.\n\nVariance: \\(\\sigma^2 = \\frac{24.39}{6} - 1.95^2 = 4.065 - 3.8025 = 0.2625\\) kgВІ.' },
      { q: 'Explain why the interquartile range is often preferred over the range as a measure of spread, and state one disadvantage of the IQR.', marks: 3, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'The IQR is preferred over the range because the range is greatly affected by extreme values or outliers вҖ” a single unusually large or small value will make the range very large and unrepresentative. The IQR measures the spread of the middle 50% of the data, so it is resistant to outliers and extreme values.\n\nDisadvantage of IQR: It ignores the 25% of values at each end of the distribution, so it does not use all the data. This means it may miss important variation at the extremes.' },
    ],
    red: [
      { q: 'The grouped frequency table shows the distances (km) travelled to work by 80 employees:\n| Distance | Frequency |\n|----------|-----------|\n| 0 вүӨ d < 5 | 12 |\n| 5 вүӨ d < 10 | 18 |\n| 10 вүӨ d < 20 | 24 |\n| 20 вүӨ d < 30 | 16 |\n| 30 вүӨ d < 50 | 10 |\n\nCalculate an estimate of the mean and standard deviation of the distances travelled.', marks: 7, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: 'Midpoints: 2.5, 7.5, 15, 25, 40.\n\n\\(\\sum fm = 12(2.5)+18(7.5)+24(15)+16(25)+10(40)\\)\n\\(= 30+135+360+400+400 = 1325\\)\n\nMean: \\(\\bar{x} = \\frac{1325}{80} = 16.5625 \\approx 16.6\\) km.\n\n\\(\\sum fm^2 = 12(6.25)+18(56.25)+24(225)+16(625)+10(1600)\\)\n\\(= 75+1012.5+5400+10000+16000 = 32487.5\\)\n\nVariance: \\(\\sigma^2 = \\frac{32487.5}{80} - 16.5625^2 = 406.09375 - 274.32...= 131.77\\)\n\nStandard deviation: \\(\\sigma = \\sqrt{131.77} \\approx 11.48\\) km.' },
      { q: 'Two data sets are summarised below:\nSet A: \\(n=30\\), \\(\\sum x = 720\\), \\(\\sum x^2 = 18500\\)\nSet B: \\(n=20\\), \\(\\sum x = 440\\), \\(\\sum x^2 = 10800\\)\n\n(a) Calculate the mean and standard deviation for each set.\n(b) Compare the two sets in terms of location and spread.\n(c) Calculate the combined mean of both data sets.', marks: 8, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: '(a) Set A:\n\\(\\bar{x}_A = \\frac{720}{30} = 24\\)\n\\(\\sigma_A^2 = \\frac{18500}{30} - 24^2 = 616.67 - 576 = 40.67\\)\n\\(\\sigma_A = \\sqrt{40.67} \\approx 6.38\\)\n\nSet B:\n\\(\\bar{x}_B = \\frac{440}{20} = 22\\)\n\\(\\sigma_B^2 = \\frac{10800}{20} - 22^2 = 540 - 484 = 56\\)\n\\(\\sigma_B = \\sqrt{56} \\approx 7.48\\)\n\n(b) Set A has a higher mean (24 vs 22), so typical values are higher in Set A. Set B has a larger standard deviation (7.48 vs 6.38), so Set B is more spread out / less consistent.\n\n(c) Combined mean \\(= \\frac{720+440}{30+20} = \\frac{1160}{50} = 23.2\\).' },
      { q: 'The following data shows the number of hours of sunshine per day during August at a seaside resort, summarised by: minimum = 3.2, \\(Q_1 = 5.8\\), median = 7.1, \\(Q_3 = 9.4\\), maximum = 14.2.\n\n(a) Construct a box plot for this data.\n(b) Describe the skewness of the distribution with full justification.\n(c) Identify any potential outliers using the \\(1.5 \\times \\text{IQR}\\) rule.', marks: 7, tier: 'red', diagram: true, modelAnswer: '(a) Box plot: draw a number line from 0 to 15. Box from 5.8 to 9.4, line at 7.1. Whiskers from 3.2 to 14.2.\n\n(b) Skewness check:\n\\(Q_2 - Q_1 = 7.1 - 5.8 = 1.3\\)\n\\(Q_3 - Q_2 = 9.4 - 7.1 = 2.3\\)\n\nSince \\(Q_3 - Q_2 > Q_2 - Q_1\\), the distribution is positively skewed. The upper half of the middle 50% is more spread out than the lower half, and the right tail is longer.\n\n(c) IQR = 9.4 вҲ’ 5.8 = 3.6.\nUpper fence = 9.4 + 1.5(3.6) = 9.4 + 5.4 = 14.8.\nLower fence = 5.8 вҲ’ 5.4 = 0.4.\n\nMaximum = 14.2 < 14.8 вң“ not an outlier.\nMinimum = 3.2 > 0.4 вң“ not an outlier.\n\nThere are no outliers.' },
      { q: 'A researcher collects data on the salary (ВЈ000s) of 100 employees. The data is summarised below:\n| Salary (ВЈ000s) | Frequency |\n|----------------|-----------|\n| 20 вүӨ s < 25 | 10 |\n| 25 вүӨ s < 30 | 22 |\n| 30 вүӨ s < 35 | 30 |\n| 35 вүӨ s < 45 | 24 |\n| 45 вүӨ s < 65 | 14 |\n\n(a) Calculate an estimate of the mean and variance.\n(b) Comment on the shape of the distribution and justify your answer.', marks: 8, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: '(a) Midpoints: 22.5, 27.5, 32.5, 40, 55.\n\n\\(\\sum fm = 10(22.5)+22(27.5)+30(32.5)+24(40)+14(55)\\)\n\\(= 225+605+975+960+770 = 3535\\)\n\nMean: \\(\\bar{x} = \\frac{3535}{100} = 35.35\\) (ВЈ000s).\n\n\\(\\sum fm^2 = 10(506.25)+22(756.25)+30(1056.25)+24(1600)+14(3025)\\)\n\\(= 5062.5+16637.5+31687.5+38400+42350 = 134137.5\\)\n\nVariance: \\(\\sigma^2 = \\frac{134137.5}{100} - 35.35^2 = 1341.375 - 1249.6225 = 91.75\\)\n\n(b) The class widths are unequal вҖ” the last two classes are wider (10 and 20 vs 5). The high mean relative to the lower classes, and the wider upper classes containing a combined 38% of data, suggest the distribution is positively skewed. Salary distributions typically have a long right tail because a small number of high earners pull the mean above the median.' },
      { q: 'Describe how you would use a stem-and-leaf diagram to compare two data sets, and explain two advantages of stem-and-leaf diagrams over box plots.', marks: 5, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: 'A back-to-back stem-and-leaf diagram has a shared central stem with one data set\'s leaves on the left and the other\'s on the right. This allows direct visual comparison of the distributions.\n\nTo compare: read the shape, spread, and typical values from each side. Calculate medians and ranges directly from the leaves.\n\nAdvantage 1: A stem-and-leaf diagram shows every individual data value, whereas a box plot only shows 5-number summary. This means no information is lost and the exact distribution shape (e.g. gaps or clusters) is visible.\n\nAdvantage 2: The median and quartiles can be found exactly from a stem-and-leaf diagram without any estimation, whereas a box plot only displays these values without showing the underlying data.' },
      { q: 'A teacher records the test scores (out of 50) for two groups of students:\nGroup 1 (n=10): 23, 28, 31, 34, 35, 37, 38, 40, 44, 48\nGroup 2 (n=10): 15, 20, 25, 30, 35, 36, 40, 42, 45, 50\n\nCalculate the mean and standard deviation for each group and write a full comparison of the two groups\' performance.', marks: 8, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: 'Group 1:\n\\(\\sum x = 23+28+31+34+35+37+38+40+44+48 = 358\\)\n\\(\\bar{x}_1 = 35.8\\)\n\\(\\sum x^2 = 529+784+961+1156+1225+1369+1444+1600+1936+2304 = 13308\\)\n\\(\\sigma_1^2 = \\frac{13308}{10} - 35.8^2 = 1330.8 - 1281.64 = 49.16\\)\n\\(\\sigma_1 = \\sqrt{49.16} \\approx 7.01\\)\n\nGroup 2:\n\\(\\sum x = 15+20+25+30+35+36+40+42+45+50 = 338\\)\n\\(\\bar{x}_2 = 33.8\\)\n\\(\\sum x^2 = 225+400+625+900+1225+1296+1600+1764+2025+2500 = 12560\\)\n\\(\\sigma_2^2 = \\frac{12560}{10} - 33.8^2 = 1256 - 1142.44 = 113.56\\)\n\\(\\sigma_2 = \\sqrt{113.56} \\approx 10.66\\)\n\nComparison:\nGroup 1 has a higher mean (35.8 > 33.8), so Group 1 performed slightly better on average.\nGroup 2 has a much larger standard deviation (10.66 > 7.01), indicating Group 2\'s scores are considerably more spread out вҖ” a wider range of abilities.\nGroup 1 is more consistent in performance. Group 2 has both the lowest (15) and highest (50) scores, suggesting a more varied ability range.' },
      { q: 'Explain what a <strong>histogram</strong> represents and describe how you would use it to estimate the median of a data set. Use the following data:\n| Class | Frequency |\n|---------|-----------|\n| 0 вүӨ x < 10 | 5 |\n| 10 вүӨ x < 20 | 15 |\n| 20 вүӨ x < 30 | 25 |\n| 30 вүӨ x < 40 | 20 |\n| 40 вүӨ x < 60 | 10 |', marks: 7, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: 'A histogram represents the distribution of continuous data, where the area of each bar equals the frequency (or relative frequency) of that class. The vertical axis shows frequency density (= frequency Г· class width).\n\nTo estimate the median: the total frequency is 5+15+25+20+10 = 75. The median is the \\(\\frac{75+1}{2} = 38\\text{th}\\) value.\n\nCumulative frequencies:\n0вҖ“10: 5\n0вҖ“20: 20\n0вҖ“30: 45 (median lies in 20вҖ“30 class)\n\nMedian lies in class 20 вүӨ x < 30.\n\nUsing linear interpolation:\nNeed 38th value. By end of class 20 we have 20, so need 38 вҲ’ 20 = 18 more into the class of 25.\n\n\\(\\text{Median} \\approx 20 + \\frac{18}{25} \\times 10 = 20 + 7.2 = 27.2\\)' },
      { q: 'The following data shows the heights of 12 plants (cm): 8, 10, 12, 14, 15, 17, 18, 20, 22, 25, 27, 44.\n\n(a) Calculate the mean, median, and IQR.\n(b) Using the \\(1.5 \\times \\text{IQR}\\) rule, determine whether 44 is an outlier.\n(c) Discuss the effect of removing 44 from the data set on the mean and median. Which measure is more appropriate?', marks: 8, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: '(a) \\(\\bar{x} = \\frac{8+10+12+14+15+17+18+20+22+25+27+44}{12} = \\frac{232}{12} \\approx 19.33\\) cm.\n\nMedian: mean of 6th and 7th values = \\(\\frac{17+18}{2} = 17.5\\) cm.\n\n\\(Q_1\\): median of lower 6 (8,10,12,14,15,17) = \\(\\frac{12+14}{2} = 13\\)\n\\(Q_3\\): median of upper 6 (18,20,22,25,27,44) = \\(\\frac{22+25}{2} = 23.5\\)\nIQR = 23.5 вҲ’ 13 = 10.5\n\n(b) Upper fence = 23.5 + 1.5(10.5) = 23.5 + 15.75 = 39.25.\nSince 44 > 39.25, the value 44 IS an outlier.\n\n(c) Without 44 (n=11): \\(\\bar{x}_{new} = \\frac{232-44}{11} = \\frac{188}{11} \\approx 17.09\\) cm (drops by about 2.24).\n\nMedian without 44: 6th value of 11 = 17 cm (barely changes from 17.5).\n\nThe median is more appropriate because it is barely affected by the outlier, whereas the mean is significantly inflated by the extreme value of 44 cm.' },
      { q: 'Describe the process of <strong>coding data</strong> and explain why it simplifies calculations. Given \\(y = \\frac{x-100}{5}\\), if coded data gives \\(\\bar{y} = 3.2\\) and \\(\\sigma_y = 2.4\\), find the original mean and standard deviation.', marks: 6, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: 'Coding data involves applying a linear transformation \\(y = \\frac{x-a}{b}\\) to the original data. This shifts and scales the values to produce smaller, easier numbers to work with. The mean and standard deviation of \\(y\\) can be found from coded data, then reverse-transformed.\n\nGiven \\(y = \\frac{x-100}{5}\\):\n\nReverse transformation: \\(x = 5y + 100\\).\n\nOriginal mean: \\(\\bar{x} = 5\\bar{y} + 100 = 5(3.2) + 100 = 16 + 100 = 116\\).\n\nOriginal standard deviation: The \\(+100\\) shift does not affect the spread, but the \\(\\times 5\\) scaling multiplies the SD.\n\\(\\sigma_x = 5 \\times \\sigma_y = 5 \\times 2.4 = 12\\).' },
      { q: 'Two factories produce bolts. A quality control inspector measures bolt diameters (mm).\nFactory A: mean = 10.02, SD = 0.08, sample size = 50.\nFactory B: mean = 10.05, SD = 0.15, sample size = 50.\n\n(a) Calculate the combined mean diameter.\n(b) Compare the quality of the two factories\' output in terms of accuracy (closeness to target of 10.00 mm) and consistency.\n(c) Which factory would you recommend for a precision engineering application? Justify.', marks: 7, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: '(a) Combined mean \\(= \\frac{50(10.02)+50(10.05)}{100} = \\frac{501+502.5}{100} = \\frac{1003.5}{100} = 10.035\\) mm.\n\n(b) Accuracy: Factory A\'s mean (10.02) is closer to the target of 10.00 mm than Factory B\'s mean (10.05). Both are slightly above target, but Factory A deviates by only 0.02 mm vs 0.05 mm for Factory B.\n\nConsistency: Factory A has a much smaller standard deviation (0.08 vs 0.15), meaning its bolts are much more consistently sized with less variation around the mean.\n\n(c) Factory A should be recommended. It produces bolts that are closer to the target diameter and much more consistent. In precision engineering, both accuracy (mean close to target) and consistency (small SD) are critical. Factory B\'s larger spread means more bolts will fall outside acceptable tolerances.' },
    ],
  },

  // в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җ
  // S3: Probability
  // в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җ
  'S3': {
    name: 'Probability',
    green: [
      { q: 'A bag contains 5 red, 3 blue, and 2 green balls. A ball is chosen at random. Find the probability it is (a) red, (b) not blue.', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'Total = 10 balls.\n(a) \\(P(\\text{red}) = \\frac{5}{10} = \\frac{1}{2}\\)\n(b) \\(P(\\text{not blue}) = 1 - \\frac{3}{10} = \\frac{7}{10}\\)' },
      { q: 'Events A and B: \\(P(A)=0.4\\), \\(P(B)=0.3\\), \\(P(A\\cup B)=0.6\\). Find \\(P(A\\cap B)\\).', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'Addition rule: \\(P(A\\cup B)=P(A)+P(B)-P(A\\cap B)\\). So \\(0.6=0.7-P(A\\cap B)\\), giving \\(P(A\\cap B)=0.1\\).' },
      { q: 'Mutually exclusive events: \\(P(A)=0.35\\), \\(P(B)=0.25\\). Find \\(P(A\\cup B)\\).', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: '\\(P(A\\cap B)=0\\). \\(P(A\\cup B)=0.35+0.25=0.60\\).' },
      { q: 'Draw a Venn diagram for events A and B where \\(P(A)=0.5\\), \\(P(B)=0.4\\), \\(P(A\\cap B)=0.2\\). Label all four regions.', marks: 3, tier: 'green', diagram: true, modelAnswer: 'Only A: 0.5вҲ’0.2=0.3. Only B: 0.4вҲ’0.2=0.2. Both: 0.2. Neither: 1вҲ’0.3вҲ’0.2вҲ’0.2=0.3. Draw two overlapping circles inside a rectangle, label regions 0.3, 0.2, 0.2, 0.3. Check sum=1.' },
      { q: 'A fair die is rolled. \\(A=\\{\\text{even}\\}\\), \\(B=\\{\\text{score}>4\\}\\). Find \\(P(A\\cap B)\\).', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: '\\(A=\\{2,4,6\\}\\), \\(B=\\{5,6\\}\\). \\(A\\cap B=\\{6\\}\\). \\(P(A\\cap B)=\\frac{1}{6}\\).' },
      { q: 'Draw a tree diagram: flip a fair coin, then classify a die roll as odd or even. Label all branches with probabilities.', marks: 3, tier: 'green', diagram: true, modelAnswer: 'First branch: H(\\(\\frac{1}{2}\\)), T(\\(\\frac{1}{2}\\)). From each: Odd(\\(\\frac{1}{2}\\)), Even(\\(\\frac{1}{2}\\)). Four outcomes each with probability \\(\\frac{1}{4}\\). Sum=1 вң“' },
      { q: 'A card is drawn from 52 cards. Find \\(P(\\text{King})\\), \\(P(\\text{heart})\\), \\(P(\\text{King or heart})\\).', marks: 3, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: '\\(P(\\text{King})=\\frac{4}{52}=\\frac{1}{13}\\). \\(P(\\text{heart})=\\frac{13}{52}=\\frac{1}{4}\\). \\(P(\\text{King or heart})=\\frac{4+13-1}{52}=\\frac{16}{52}=\\frac{4}{13}\\).' },
      { q: '\\(P(A)=0.6\\), \\(P(B|A)=0.3\\). Find \\(P(A\\cap B)\\).', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: '\\(P(A\\cap B)=P(B|A)\\times P(A)=0.3\\times 0.6=0.18\\).' },
      { q: 'State what it means for events to be mutually exclusive. Give a practical example.', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'Two events are mutually exclusive if they cannot both occur: \\(P(A\\cap B)=0\\). Example: on a single die roll, scoring 2 and scoring 5 are mutually exclusive.' },
      { q: 'A discrete random variable \\(X\\) has \\(P(X=1)=0.2\\), \\(P(X=2)=0.3\\), \\(P(X=3)=0.4\\), \\(P(X=4)=0.1\\). Find \\(E(X)\\).', marks: 3, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: '\\(E(X)=1(0.2)+2(0.3)+3(0.4)+4(0.1)=0.2+0.6+1.2+0.4=2.4\\).' },
      { q: 'A bag has 4 white and 6 black balls. Two drawn without replacement. Draw a tree diagram and find \\(P(\\text{both white})\\).', marks: 3, tier: 'green', diagram: true, modelAnswer: 'First draw: \\(P(W)=\\frac{4}{10}\\), \\(P(B)=\\frac{6}{10}\\). Given first W: \\(P(W)=\\frac{3}{9}\\). \\(P(\\text{both white})=\\frac{4}{10}\\times\\frac{3}{9}=\\frac{12}{90}=\\frac{2}{15}\\).' },
      { q: '\\(P(A)=0.5\\), \\(P(B)=0.4\\), A and B independent. Find \\(P(A\\cap B)\\) and \\(P(A\\cup B)\\).', marks: 3, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: '\\(P(A\\cap B)=0.5\\times 0.4=0.2\\). \\(P(A\\cup B)=0.5+0.4-0.2=0.7\\).' },
      { q: 'X takes values 1,2,3,4 with \\(P(X=x)=kx\\). Find \\(k\\).', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'Sum of probabilities: \\(k(1+2+3+4)=10k=1\\), so \\(k=0.1\\).' },
      { q: 'Show using a Venn diagram that if \\(P(A)=0.6\\), \\(P(B)=0.5\\), \\(P(A\\cap B)=0.3\\), then \\(P(A^\\prime\\cap B^\\prime)=0.2\\).', marks: 3, tier: 'green', diagram: true, modelAnswer: 'Only A: 0.3. Only B: 0.2. Both: 0.3. Neither: 1вҲ’0.3вҲ’0.2вҲ’0.3=0.2. Label all four Venn regions to verify the result.' },
      { q: 'A fair coin is flipped 3 times. Find \\(P(\\text{exactly 2 heads})\\).', marks: 3, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'All 8 outcomes equally likely. Exactly 2 heads: HHT, HTH, THH вҖ” 3 outcomes. \\(P=\\frac{3}{8}\\).' },
    ],
    amber: [
      { q: '\\(P(A)=0.45\\), \\(P(B)=0.30\\), \\(P(A\\cap B)=0.12\\). Find (a)\\(P(A|B)\\), (b)\\(P(B|A)\\), (c) are A, B independent?', marks: 5, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '(a) \\(P(A|B)=\\frac{0.12}{0.30}=0.4\\). (b) \\(P(B|A)=\\frac{0.12}{0.45}=\\frac{4}{15}\\approx 0.267\\). (c) For independence \\(P(A|B)=P(A)\\), but \\(0.4\\neq 0.45\\), so NOT independent.' },
      { q: 'Box: 5 red and 3 blue counters. Two drawn without replacement. (a) Draw tree diagram. (b) Find \\(P(\\text{both same colour})\\). (c) Find \\(P(\\text{first red}|\\text{different colours})\\).', marks: 6, tier: 'amber', diagram: true, modelAnswer: '(a) First R:5/8, B:3/8. Given R: R:4/7,B:3/7. Given B: R:5/7,B:2/7.\n(b) P(RR)=20/56, P(BB)=6/56. P(same)=26/56=13/28.\n(c) P(diff)=15/28. P(first R вҲ© diff)=P(RB)=15/56. P(first R|diff)=15/56Г·15/28=1/2.' },
      { q: 'X has: \\(P(X=0)=0.1\\), \\(P(X=1)=0.3\\), \\(P(X=2)=0.4\\), \\(P(X=3)=0.2\\). Find (a)\\(E(X)\\), (b)\\(E(X^2)\\), (c)\\(\\text{Var}(X)\\).', marks: 5, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '(a) \\(E(X)=0(0.1)+1(0.3)+2(0.4)+3(0.2)=1.7\\). (b) \\(E(X^2)=0+0.3+1.6+1.8=3.7\\). (c) \\(\\text{Var}(X)=3.7-1.7^2=3.7-2.89=0.81\\).' },
      { q: 'Three events A,B,C in a Venn diagram: only A=0.1, only B=0.15, only C=0.2, AвҲ©B only=0.1, AвҲ©C only=0.05, BвҲ©C only=0.1, AвҲ©BвҲ©C=0.05. Find P(A), P(B), P(C).', marks: 5, tier: 'amber', diagram: true, modelAnswer: 'P(A)=0.1+0.1+0.05+0.05=0.30. P(B)=0.15+0.1+0.1+0.05=0.40. P(C)=0.2+0.05+0.1+0.05=0.40. Outside all=0.25. Check sum=1.' },
      { q: 'Factory: M1 produces 60% of items (3% defective), M2 produces 40% (5% defective). (a) Draw tree diagram. (b) Find \\(P(\\text{item defective})\\).', marks: 5, tier: 'amber', diagram: true, modelAnswer: '(a) First: P(M1)=0.6,P(M2)=0.4. From M1: P(D)=0.03. From M2: P(D)=0.05.\n(b) P(D)=0.6(0.03)+0.4(0.05)=0.018+0.020=0.038.' },
      { q: '\\(E(X)=3\\), \\(E(X^2)=11\\). Find \\(\\text{Var}(X)\\) and \\(\\text{Var}(2X+1)\\).', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '\\(\\text{Var}(X)=11-9=2\\). \\(\\text{Var}(2X+1)=4\\text{Var}(X)=8\\). (Adding a constant does not change variance; multiplying X by 2 multiplies variance by \\(2^2=4\\).)' },
      { q: '\\(P(A)=0.5\\), \\(P(A\\cup B)=0.8\\), \\(P(A\\cap B)=0.2\\). Find \\(P(B)\\), \\(P(A|B)\\), \\(P(B|A)\\), and test independence.', marks: 5, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'P(B)=0.8вҲ’0.5+0.2=0.5. P(A|B)=0.2/0.5=0.4. P(B|A)=0.2/0.5=0.4. For independence: \\(P(A)P(B)=0.25\\neq0.2\\), so NOT independent.' },
      { q: '70% of adults own a car C, 40% own a bike B, 25% own both. (a) Complete a Venn diagram. (b) \\(P(C|B)\\). (c) Are C and B independent?', marks: 5, tier: 'amber', diagram: true, modelAnswer: '(a) Only C:0.45, Only B:0.15, Both:0.25, Neither:0.15.\n(b) P(C|B)=0.25/0.40=0.625.\n(c) P(C)P(B)=0.7Г—0.4=0.28вү 0.25=P(CвҲ©B), so NOT independent.' },
      { q: '\\(X\\) takes values 1вҖ“5 with probabilities proportional to \\(x\\). Find the distribution, \\(E(X)\\), and \\(\\text{Var}(X)\\).', marks: 5, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '\\(15k=1\\Rightarrow k=1/15\\). \\(P(X=x)=x/15\\).\n\\(E(X)=\\frac{1+4+9+16+25}{15}=\\frac{55}{15}=\\frac{11}{3}\\approx 3.67\\).\n\\(E(X^2)=\\frac{1+8+27+64+125}{15}=\\frac{225}{15}=15\\).\n\\(\\text{Var}(X)=15-(11/3)^2=14/9\\approx 1.56\\).' },
      { q: 'Box has 3 red and 2 blue balls. A ball is drawn and replaced. Find \\(P(\\text{both red in 2 draws})\\).', marks: 3, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'With replacement, draws are independent. \\(P(R)=3/5\\) each time. \\(P(\\text{both red})=(3/5)^2=9/25=0.36\\).' },
      { q: 'Show that \\(P(A)=P(A\\cap B)+P(A\\cap B^\\prime)\\).', marks: 3, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '\\(B\\) and \\(B^\\prime\\) partition the sample space. So \\(A=(A\\cap B)\\cup(A\\cap B^\\prime)\\) is a disjoint union. By the addition rule for mutually exclusive events: \\(P(A)=P(A\\cap B)+P(A\\cap B^\\prime)\\). вң“' },
      { q: '\\(E(X)=2.5\\), \\(\\text{Var}(X)=1.2\\). Find \\(E(3X-2)\\) and \\(\\text{Var}(3X-2)\\).', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '\\(E(3X-2)=3(2.5)-2=5.5\\). \\(\\text{Var}(3X-2)=9\\text{Var}(X)=9(1.2)=10.8\\).' },
      { q: 'Biased coin \\(P(H)=0.6\\), flipped 3 times. Draw tree diagram and find \\(P(\\text{exactly 2 heads})\\).', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', diagram: true, modelAnswer: 'P(HHT)=P(HTH)=P(THH)=0.6Г—0.6Г—0.4=0.144 each. \\(P(\\text{exactly 2 heads})=3\\times0.144=0.432\\).' },
      { q: 'Two fair dice rolled. Find \\(P(\\text{sum}=7)\\) and \\(P(\\text{sum}>9)\\).', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '36 equally likely outcomes. Sum=7: (1,6)(2,5)(3,4)(4,3)(5,2)(6,1)=6. P=1/6. Sum>9: sums 10(3),11(2),12(1)=6. P=6/36=1/6.' },
      { q: '\\(P(A)=0.3\\), \\(P(B|A)=0.5\\), \\(P(B|A^\\prime)=0.2\\). Find \\(P(B)\\) and \\(P(A|B)\\).', marks: 5, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '\\(P(B)=P(B|A)P(A)+P(B|A^\\prime)P(A^\\prime)=0.5(0.3)+0.2(0.7)=0.15+0.14=0.29\\).\n\\(P(A|B)=\\frac{P(B|A)P(A)}{P(B)}=\\frac{0.15}{0.29}\\approx 0.517\\).' },
    ],
    red: [
      { q: 'X: P(X=1)=0.05, P(X=2)=a, P(X=3)=0.30, P(X=4)=b, P(X=5)=0.15. Given E(X)=3.2, find a, b and Var(X).', marks: 7, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: 'Eq1: a+b=0.50. Eq2: 2a+4b=1.5 вҶ’ a+2b=0.75. Subtract: b=0.25, a=0.25.\nE(XВІ)=0.05+1+2.7+4+3.75=11.5. Var(X)=11.5вҲ’3.2ВІ=11.5вҲ’10.24=1.26.' },
      { q: 'A,C mutually exclusive; B,C independent. P(A)=0.3, P(B)=0.4, P(C)=0.2, P(AвҲ©B)=0.1. (a) Venn diagram. (b) P(AвҲӘB). (c) P(BвҲ©C). (d) P((AвҲӘB)вҖІ).', marks: 8, tier: 'red', diagram: true, modelAnswer: '(a) Draw three circles: A and C separate (no overlap); B overlaps both A and C.\n(b) P(AвҲӘB)=0.3+0.4вҲ’0.1=0.6.\n(c) P(BвҲ©C)=0.4Г—0.2=0.08 (independent).\n(d) P((AвҲӘB)вҖІ)=1вҲ’0.6=0.4.' },
      { q: 'Prove that if A and B are independent, then A and BвҖІ are also independent.', marks: 6, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: 'Need: P(AвҲ©BвҖІ)=P(A)P(BвҖІ).\nBy partition: P(A)=P(AвҲ©B)+P(AвҲ©BвҖІ).\nSo P(AвҲ©BвҖІ)=P(A)вҲ’P(AвҲ©B)=P(A)вҲ’P(A)P(B)=P(A)(1вҲ’P(B))=P(A)P(BвҖІ). вң“' },
      { q: 'X = emails per hour: P(X=0)=0.1, P(X=1)=0.2, P(X=2)=0.4, P(X=3)=0.2, P(X=4)=0.1. (a) E(X) and Var(X). (b) P(total in 2 independent hours > 5).', marks: 7, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: '(a) E(X)=2.0. E(XВІ)=5.2. Var(X)=1.2.\n(b) TotalвүҘ6: pairs (2,4),(4,2),(3,3),(3,4),(4,3),(4,4).\nP(sum=6)=2(0.4)(0.1)+(0.2)ВІ=0.12. P(sum=7)=2(0.2)(0.1)=0.04. P(sum=8)=0.01. P(total>5)=0.17.' },
      { q: 'Medical test: P(+|disease)=0.95, P(+|no disease)=0.08. Prevalence=2%. (a) Tree diagram. (b) P(positive). (c) P(disease|positive).', marks: 8, tier: 'red', diagram: true, modelAnswer: '(a) Disease(0.02):+(0.95),вҲ’(0.05). No disease(0.98):+(0.08),вҲ’(0.92).\n(b) P(+)=0.02(0.95)+0.98(0.08)=0.019+0.0784=0.0974.\n(c) P(D|+)=0.019/0.0974вүҲ0.195. Only ~19.5% of positives actually have the disease.' },
      { q: 'Game: roll 1/2вҶ’win ВЈ3; roll 3/4вҶ’win ВЈ1; roll 5/6вҶ’lose ВЈ2. (a) Distribution of winnings X. (b) E(X), Var(X). (c) Is the game fair?', marks: 7, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: '(a) P(X=3)=P(X=1)=P(X=вҲ’2)=1/3.\n(b) E(X)=(3+1вҲ’2)/3=2/3. E(XВІ)=(9+1+4)/3=14/3. Var(X)=14/3вҲ’4/9=38/9вүҲ4.22.\n(c) Not fair: E(X)=2/3>0, so player wins on average. A fair game requires E(X)=0.' },
      { q: 'Components A (passes 0.9) and B (passes 0.85) both needed, independent. (a) P(product passes). (b) P(exactly 2 of 3 products pass). (c) E(passing in 10).', marks: 7, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: '(a) P=0.9Г—0.85=0.765.\n(b) P=\\(\\binom{3}{2}\\)(0.765)ВІ(0.235)=3Г—0.5852Г—0.235вүҲ0.413.\n(c) E=10Г—0.765=7.65.' },
      { q: 'P(AвҲӘB)=0.9, P(A)=p, P(B)=q. (a) If mutually exclusive, equation for p+q. (b) If independent, equation. (c) If p=2q and independent, find p and q.', marks: 7, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: '(a) p+q=0.9.\n(b) p+qвҲ’pq=0.9.\n(c) p=2q: 3qвҲ’2qВІ=0.9. 2qВІвҲ’3q+0.9=0. q=(3ВұвҲҡ1.8)/4. qвүҲ0.414 (accept), pвүҲ0.829. (Other root >1, reject.)' },
      { q: 'Bag: 3 red, 4 white, 5 blue. Three drawn without replacement. (a) P(all same colour). (b) P(at least one red). (c) P(exactly two white).', marks: 8, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: '(a) P(all R)=6/1320, P(all W)=24/1320, P(all B)=60/1320. P(same)=90/1320=3/44.\n(b) P(no red)=\\(\\binom{9}{3}/\\binom{12}{3}\\)=84/220=21/55. P(at least one R)=34/55.\n(c) \\(\\binom{4}{2}\\binom{8}{1}/\\binom{12}{3}\\)=48/220=12/55.' },
      { q: 'Survey: Male(Drive 48, PT 32), Female(Drive 36, PT 44), Total 160. (a) P(female|drives). (b) Are gender and transport independent? (c) P(drives|male).', marks: 7, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: '(a) P(female|drives)=36/84=3/7вүҲ0.429.\n(b) P(drives)=84/160=0.525. P(drives|male)=48/80=0.6вү 0.525, so NOT independent.\n(c) P(drives|male)=48/80=0.6.' },
      { q: 'Two events A and B: P(A)=0.6, P(B)=0.5. P(AвҲ©B)=0.4. (a) Find P(AвҲӘB). (b) Test independence. (c) Find P(AвҖІвҲ©B).', marks: 6, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: '(a) P(AвҲӘB)=0.6+0.5вҲ’0.4=0.7.\n(b) P(A)P(B)=0.6Г—0.5=0.3вү 0.4=P(AвҲ©B), so NOT independent.\n(c) P(AвҖІвҲ©B)=P(B)вҲ’P(AвҲ©B)=0.5вҲ’0.4=0.1.' },
    ],
  },


  // в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җ
  // S4: Binomial Distribution
  // в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җ
  'S4': {
    name: 'Binomial Distribution',
    green: [
      { q: 'State the four conditions required for a random variable to follow a binomial distribution.', marks: 4, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: '1. Fixed number of trials n.\n2. Each trial results in success or failure only.\n3. The probability of success p is constant for each trial.\n4. Trials are independent of each other.' },
      { q: 'A fair coin is flipped 8 times. X = number of heads. State the distribution and find \\(P(X=3)\\).', marks: 3, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: '\\(X\\sim B(8,0.5)\\). \\(P(X=3)=\\binom{8}{3}(0.5)^8=56/256=7/32\\approx 0.2188\\).' },
      { q: '\\(X\\sim B(10,0.3)\\). Find \\(P(X=4)\\).', marks: 3, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: '\\(P(X=4)=\\binom{10}{4}(0.3)^4(0.7)^6=210\\times0.0081\\times0.117649\\approx 0.2001\\).' },
      { q: '\\(X\\sim B(12,0.25)\\). Use your calculator to find \\(P(X\\leq 3)\\).', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: '\\(P(X\\leq 3)=0.6488\\) (binomial CDF, n=12, p=0.25, k=3).' },
      { q: '\\(X\\sim B(15,0.4)\\). Find the mean and variance.', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: '\\(E(X)=np=15\\times0.4=6\\). \\(\\text{Var}(X)=np(1-p)=15\\times0.4\\times0.6=3.6\\).' },
      { q: 'A biased die has probability 0.2 of showing a 6. Rolled 10 times. Find \\(P(\\text{exactly 2 sixes})\\).', marks: 3, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: '\\(X\\sim B(10,0.2)\\). \\(P(X=2)=\\binom{10}{2}(0.2)^2(0.8)^8=45\\times0.04\\times0.1678\\approx 0.3020\\).' },
      { q: '\\(X\\sim B(20,0.35)\\). Find \\(P(X=0)\\).', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: '\\(P(X=0)=(0.65)^{20}\\approx 0.00203\\).' },
      { q: 'State the mean and variance of \\(B(n,p)\\) and evaluate them for \\(B(30,0.6)\\).', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'Mean=np=18. Var=np(1-p)=30Г—0.6Г—0.4=7.2.' },
      { q: '\\(X\\sim B(8,0.45)\\). Find \\(P(X\\leq 4)\\) and \\(P(X\\leq 2)\\) using a calculator.', marks: 3, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: '\\(P(X\\leq 4)=0.6836\\). \\(P(X\\leq 2)=0.1239\\).' },
      { q: 'A 10-question multiple-choice test has 4 options per question. A student guesses every answer. Find \\(P(\\text{at least 1 correct})\\).', marks: 3, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: '\\(X\\sim B(10,0.25)\\). \\(P(X\\geq1)=1-(0.75)^{10}=1-0.0563=0.9437\\).' },
      { q: '\\(X\\sim B(n,p)\\) with mean 6 and variance 4.2. Find n and p.', marks: 3, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'np=6, np(1-p)=4.2. Dividing: 1-p=0.7, p=0.3. n=6/0.3=20.' },
      { q: 'A treatment is effective for 70% of patients. Find \\(P(\\text{effective for exactly 4 of 6})\\).', marks: 3, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: '\\(X\\sim B(6,0.7)\\). \\(P(X=4)=\\binom{6}{4}(0.7)^4(0.3)^2=15\\times0.2401\\times0.09\\approx0.3241\\).' },
      { q: '\\(X\\sim B(5,0.3)\\). List all probabilities \\(P(X=0)\\) to \\(P(X=5)\\) to 4 d.p.', marks: 4, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'P(0)=0.1681, P(1)=0.3602, P(2)=0.3087, P(3)=0.1323, P(4)=0.0284, P(5)=0.0024. Check sumвүҲ1.' },
      { q: 'Explain why X = number of draws until first red ball from a bag of 5R+5B without replacement is NOT binomial.', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'Not binomial because: (1) the number of trials is not fixed вҖ” it varies depending on when the first red is drawn; (2) the probability of red changes with each draw (without replacement). Both the fixed n and constant p conditions are violated.' },
      { q: '\\(X\\sim B(10,0.5)\\). Find \\(P(X=5)\\) and comment on the symmetry of the distribution.', marks: 3, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: '\\(P(X=5)=\\binom{10}{5}(0.5)^{10}=252/1024\\approx0.2461\\). When p=0.5, the distribution is symmetric about np=5: P(X=k)=P(X=10вҲ’k). It is a mirror image about X=5.' },
    ],
    amber: [
      { q: '\\(X\\sim B(15,0.3)\\). Find (a)\\(P(X\\geq5)\\), (b)\\(P(3\\leq X\\leq7)\\).', marks: 5, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '(a) P(XвүӨ4)=0.5155. P(XвүҘ5)=1вҲ’0.5155=0.4845.\n(b) P(XвүӨ7)=0.9500, P(XвүӨ2)=0.1268. P(3вүӨXвүӨ7)=0.9500вҲ’0.1268=0.8232.' },
      { q: 'Manufacturer claims 5% of items are defective. Quality inspector checks 20 items. (a) State distribution. (b) P(more than 2 defective). (c) Comment on binomial suitability.', marks: 5, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '(a) X~B(20,0.05).\n(b) P(X>2)=1вҲ’P(XвүӨ2). P(X=0)+P(X=1)+P(X=2)=0.9246. P(X>2)=0.0754.\n(c) Binomial appropriate if items are independent (reasonable for large batch), p constant (stable process), fixed n=20. Conditions plausibly met.' },
      { q: '\\(X\\sim B(n,0.4)\\) and \\(P(X=0)<0.05\\). Find minimum integer n.', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '\\((0.6)^n<0.05\\). Taking logs: n>ln(0.05)/ln(0.6)=5.865. Minimum n=6. Check: (0.6)^6=0.0467<0.05 вң“; (0.6)^5=0.0778>0.05 вң—.' },
      { q: '60% of students pass an exam. Random sample of 12. Find (a)P(exactly 8 pass), (b)P(fewer than half pass).', marks: 5, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '(a) X~B(12,0.6). P(X=8)=\\(\\binom{12}{8}\\)(0.6)^8(0.4)^4=495Г—0.01680Г—0.0256вүҲ0.2128.\n(b) Fewer than half: X<6, i.e. XвүӨ5. P(XвүӨ5)=0.1582.' },
      { q: '\\(X\\sim B(20,p)\\) with \\(P(X=1)=0.2702\\). Find p.', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '\\(20p(1-p)^{19}=0.2702\\). Try p=0.10: 20(0.1)(0.9)^{19}=2Г—0.1351=0.2702 вң“. So p=0.10.' },
      { q: 'In a game, player scores a point by rolling 5 or 6. 12 rolls total. (a) State distribution. (b) P(XвүҘ5). (c) E(X) and SD.', marks: 5, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '(a) p=1/3, X~B(12,1/3).\n(b) P(XвүӨ4)=0.5931. P(XвүҘ5)=0.4069.\n(c) E(X)=4. Var(X)=8/3. SD=вҲҡ(8/3)вүҲ1.633.' },
      { q: 'Explain why binomial is NOT suitable for sampling 10 from a batch of 50 items (5 known defective) without replacement. What distribution is more appropriate?', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'Not suitable: sampling without replacement means P(defective) changes each draw and draws are not independent вҖ” binomial requires constant p and independence. The hypergeometric distribution is more appropriate for sampling without replacement from a finite population with known number of defectives.' },
      { q: '\\(X\\sim B(25,0.2)\\). Find smallest k such that \\(P(X\\leq k)>0.9\\).', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'P(XвүӨ6)=0.7800, P(XвүӨ7)=0.8909, P(XвүӨ8)=0.9532>0.9 вң“. Smallest k=8.' },
      { q: 'Call centre: n=20 calls, p=0.2 complaint rate. (a) P(X=4). (b) P(X>6). (c) E(X) and Var(X).', marks: 5, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '(a) P(X=4)=\\(\\binom{20}{4}\\)(0.2)^4(0.8)^{16}вүҲ0.2182.\n(b) P(X>6)=1вҲ’P(XвүӨ6)=1вҲ’0.9133=0.0867.\n(c) E(X)=4. Var(X)=3.2.' },
      { q: '\\(X\\sim B(n,p)\\): E(X)=4, Var(X)=3. Find n and p.', marks: 3, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'np=4, np(1-p)=3. 1-p=3/4, p=1/4=0.25. n=4/0.25=16.' },
      { q: '35% of people prefer tea. Sample of 18. Find (a)P(at most 5 prefer tea), (b)P(exactly 9 prefer tea).', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '(a) X~B(18,0.35). P(XвүӨ5)=0.2717.\n(b) P(X=9)=\\(\\binom{18}{9}\\)(0.35)^9(0.65)^9вүҲ0.0794.' },
      { q: 'Describe the shape of B(n,p) when (a)p<0.5, (b)p=0.5, (c)p>0.5.', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '(a) p<0.5: positively skewed (right tail). (b) p=0.5: symmetric about np. (c) p>0.5: negatively skewed (left tail).' },
      { q: 'Fair die rolled 20 times. X=number of sixes. (a) State distribution. (b) P(XвүҘ3). (c) P(X=3|XвүӨ5).', marks: 6, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '(a) X~B(20,1/6).\n(b) P(XвүӨ2)=0.2300. P(XвүҘ3)=0.7700.\n(c) P(X=3)=\\(\\binom{20}{3}\\)(1/6)^3(5/6)^{17}вүҲ0.2379. P(XвүӨ5)=0.5652. P(X=3|XвүӨ5)=0.2379/0.5652вүҲ0.4209.' },
      { q: '\\(X\\sim B(n,0.3)\\). Find smallest n such that \\(P(X\\geq1)>0.99\\).', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '1вҲ’0.7^n>0.99. 0.7^n<0.01. n>ln(0.01)/ln(0.7)=12.91. Minimum n=13. Check: 0.7^{13}вүҲ0.00975<0.01 вң“.' },
      { q: 'Hospital treats patients independently, each with P(recovery)=0.8. 15 patients treated. Find P(exactly 12 recover) and P(at least 13 recover).', marks: 5, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'X~B(15,0.8).\nP(X=12)=\\(\\binom{15}{12}\\)(0.8)^{12}(0.2)^3=455Г—0.0687Г—0.008=0.2501.\nP(XвүҘ13)=1вҲ’P(XвүӨ12)=1вҲ’0.6020=0.3980.' },
    ],
    red: [
      { q: 'Batch of bolts: 10% defective. Sample of 25. (a) State distribution and verify conditions. (b) P(XвүӨ3). (c) Find c such that P(X>c)<0.05.', marks: 7, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: '(a) X~B(25,0.1). Conditions: fixed n=25 вң“; defective or not вң“; p=0.1 constant (large batch) вң“; independent (random selection) вң“.\n(b) P(XвүӨ3)=0.7636.\n(c) P(XвүӨ4)=0.9020<0.95. P(XвүӨ5)=0.9666>0.95. c=5.' },
      { q: 'Archer: P(hit)=0.7, 15 shots. (a) P(XвүҘ12). (b) P(missing at least 4). (c) P(X=12|XвүҘ10).', marks: 8, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: '(a) P(XвүӨ11)=0.7031. P(XвүҘ12)=0.2969.\n(b) MissingвүҘ4 means hitsвүӨ11. P(XвүӨ11)=0.7031.\n(c) P(XвүҘ10)=1вҲ’P(XвүӨ9)=1вҲ’0.2784=0.7216. P(X=12)=\\(\\binom{15}{12}\\)(0.7)^{12}(0.3)^3вүҲ0.1700. P(X=12|XвүҘ10)=0.1700/0.7216вүҲ0.2356.' },
      { q: 'Critique: "X~B(10,0.4) models goals scored in 10 minutes". Identify at least 3 flaws.', marks: 7, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: 'Flaw 1: No fixed n вҖ” goals occur continuously in time, not in a fixed number of discrete trials.\nFlaw 2: Not independent вҖ” a goal changes game state, tactics, and likelihood of further goals.\nFlaw 3: p not constant вҖ” scoring probability varies with time, scoreline, and team fatigue.\nFlaw 4: A Poisson distribution is more appropriate for rare events over continuous time.' },
      { q: 'Student A (p=0.7) and B (p=0.5) each attempt 20 questions independently. (a) P(A gets at least 15 correct). (b) If A gets exactly 14, find P(B scores fewer than A).', marks: 7, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: '(a) X_A~B(20,0.7). P(X_AвүҘ15)=1вҲ’P(X_AвүӨ14)=1вҲ’0.5836=0.4164.\n(b) X_B~B(20,0.5). P(X_BвүӨ13)=0.9423.' },
      { q: 'Fair coin tossed n times. Find minimum n so P(XвүҘ1)>0.999.', marks: 5, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: '1вҲ’(0.5)^n>0.999. (0.5)^n<0.001. n>ln(0.001)/ln(0.5)=9.97. Minimum n=10. Check: (0.5)^{10}=0.000977<0.001 вң“.' },
      { q: 'Seeds germinate with p=0.8. Tray of 30. (a) P(at least 25 germinate). (b) Assess claim p>0.8 given 27 of 30 germinate.', marks: 7, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: '(a) X~B(30,0.8). P(XвүҘ25)=1вҲ’P(XвүӨ24)=1вҲ’0.5725=0.4275.\n(b) P(XвүҘ27)=1вҲ’P(XвүӨ26)=1вҲ’0.8389=0.1611. This is 16.1%, not unusually low. Insufficient evidence at 5% to conclude p>0.8.' },
      { q: 'Find the critical region for testing HвӮҖ:p=0.45 vs HвӮҒ:p>0.45 using X~B(20,0.45) at 5% significance. State the actual significance level.', marks: 7, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: 'Need smallest c: P(XвүҘc)вүӨ0.05, i.e. P(XвүӨcвҲ’1)вүҘ0.95.\nP(XвүӨ12)=0.8585, P(XвүӨ13)=0.9270, P(XвүӨ14)=0.9699вүҘ0.95. So c=15.\nCritical region: XвүҘ15. Actual significance level=P(XвүҘ15)=1вҲ’0.9699=0.0301=3.01%.' },
      { q: 'Call centre: E(X)=7 sales from 20 calls. (a) Find p and state distribution. (b) P(XвүҘ10). (c) In new sample of 20, 12 sales occur. Find P(XвүҘ12) and comment.', marks: 8, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: '(a) 20p=7, p=0.35. X~B(20,0.35).\n(b) P(XвүҘ10)=1вҲ’P(XвүӨ9)=1вҲ’0.8782=0.1218.\n(c) P(XвүҘ12)=1вҲ’P(XвүӨ11)=1вҲ’0.9468=0.0532. Just above 5% level вҖ” borderline evidence, insufficient to conclude rate has increased at 5%.' },
      { q: 'Compare B(100,0.05) and B(100,0.5) in terms of mean, variance, SD, and shape. Explain which can be approximated by Poisson.', marks: 7, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: 'B(100,0.05): mean=5, var=4.75, SDвүҲ2.18, positively skewed.\nB(100,0.5): mean=50, var=25, SD=5, symmetric.\nPoisson approximation: B(100,0.05) can be approximated by Poisson(5) since n is large (вүҘ50) and p is small (вүӨ0.1). B(100,0.5) should use Normal(50,25) instead.' },
      { q: 'Factory: P(item faulty)=p, batch of 10. (a) Write P(X=0) in terms of p. (b) If P(X=0)=0.1074, find p. (c) Using this p, find P(1вүӨXвүӨ3).', marks: 7, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: '(a) P(X=0)=(1вҲ’p)^{10}.\n(b) (1вҲ’p)^{10}=0.1074. 1вҲ’p=0.1074^{0.1}=0.80. p=0.20.\n(c) X~B(10,0.2). P(XвүӨ3)=0.8791. P(X=0)=0.1074. P(1вүӨXвүӨ3)=0.8791вҲ’0.1074=0.7717.' },
    ],
  },


  // в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җ
  // S5: Hypothesis Testing вҖ” Binomial
  // в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җ
  'S5': {
    name: 'Hypothesis Testing вҖ” Binomial',
    green: [
      { q: 'A coin is suspected of being biased towards heads. A researcher flips it 20 times and observes 14 heads. State \\(H_0\\) and \\(H_1\\) for a one-tailed test.', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: '\\(H_0: p=0.5\\) (the coin is fair).\n\\(H_1: p>0.5\\) (the coin is biased towards heads).\n\nThis is a one-tailed test because we are specifically testing whether p is greater than 0.5.' },
      { q: 'State the difference between a one-tailed and a two-tailed hypothesis test in the context of the binomial distribution.', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'A one-tailed test tests whether the parameter has increased (HвӮҒ: p>pвӮҖ) or decreased (HвӮҒ: p<pвӮҖ) вҖ” in a specific direction.\n\nA two-tailed test tests whether the parameter has changed in either direction (HвӮҒ: pвү pвӮҖ), so the critical region is split between both tails.' },
      { q: 'In a hypothesis test with \\(H_0: p=0.4\\), \\(H_1: p<0.4\\), \\(n=15\\), and observed \\(X=3\\), find the p-value using the binomial distribution.', marks: 3, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'p-value = P(XвүӨ3) under B(15, 0.4).\nP(X=0)=0.6^{15}=0.00047\nP(X=1)=15(0.4)(0.6)^{14}=0.00469\nP(X=2)=\\(\\binom{15}{2}\\)(0.4)^2(0.6)^{13}=0.02194\nP(X=3)=\\(\\binom{15}{3}\\)(0.4)^3(0.6)^{12}=0.06340\np-value=P(XвүӨ3)=0.0905 (to 4 d.p.)' },
      { q: 'A test has \\(H_0:p=0.3\\), \\(H_1:p>0.3\\), significance level 5%, and observed X=9 from n=20. The p-value is 0.1133. Write a conclusion in context.', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'Since the p-value (0.1133) > 0.05 (significance level), we do not reject \\(H_0\\).\n\nConclusion: There is insufficient evidence at the 5% significance level to conclude that p > 0.3. The data is consistent with the null hypothesis.' },
      { q: 'State what is meant by the <em>significance level</em> of a hypothesis test.', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'The significance level is the probability of rejecting the null hypothesis when it is actually true (a Type I error). It is set before the test is conducted and defines how extreme the data must be to reject HвӮҖ. Common significance levels are 5% (0.05) and 1% (0.01).' },
      { q: 'A coin is flipped 10 times. \\(H_0:p=0.5\\), \\(H_1:p\\neq0.5\\). Observed X=9. Find the p-value for this two-tailed test.', marks: 3, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'p-value = P(XвүҘ9 or XвүӨ1) under B(10, 0.5).\nP(XвүҘ9)=P(X=9)+P(X=10)=10(0.5)^{10}+(0.5)^{10}=\\frac{11}{1024}вүҲ0.0107\nBy symmetry, P(XвүӨ1)=0.0107.\np-value=2Г—0.0107=0.0214.' },
      { q: 'State the conclusion of a hypothesis test when: p-value = 0.032, significance level = 5%.', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: '0.032 < 0.05, so we reject \\(H_0\\). There is sufficient evidence at the 5% significance level to support the alternative hypothesis.' },
      { q: 'Define the <em>critical region</em> (rejection region) in a hypothesis test.', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'The critical region is the set of values of the test statistic for which the null hypothesis would be rejected. If the observed test statistic falls within the critical region, HвӮҖ is rejected. The critical region is determined by the significance level.' },
      { q: 'For \\(X\\sim B(20,p)\\), \\(H_0:p=0.5\\), \\(H_1:p<0.5\\), significance level 5%. State whether X=6 leads to rejection of \\(H_0\\) given that P(XвүӨ6)=0.0577.', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'P(XвүӨ6)=0.0577 > 0.05. Since the p-value (0.0577) exceeds the significance level (0.05), we do NOT reject HвӮҖ. There is insufficient evidence to conclude p<0.5.' },
      { q: 'State what is meant by a <em>Type I error</em> in hypothesis testing.', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'A Type I error occurs when the null hypothesis HвӮҖ is rejected even though it is true. The probability of a Type I error equals the significance level (Оұ) of the test.' },
      { q: 'A researcher claims that fewer than 30% of adults exercise regularly. In a sample of 25 adults, 4 exercise regularly. State HвӮҖ and HвӮҒ, and identify the tail of the test.', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: '\\(H_0:p=0.3\\) (30% of adults exercise regularly).\n\\(H_1:p<0.3\\) (fewer than 30% exercise regularly).\n\nThis is a one-tailed (lower tail) test, since we are testing whether p has decreased below 0.3.' },
      { q: 'In a binomial hypothesis test, the critical value is c = 3. State what this means.', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'The critical value c=3 means that if the observed value of X is 3 or less (for a lower-tail test), HвӮҖ is rejected. The critical region is XвүӨ3. If X>3, we do not reject HвӮҖ.' },
      { q: 'For \\(X\\sim B(15,p)\\), \\(H_0:p=0.2\\), \\(H_1:p>0.2\\), at the 10% level. Given P(XвүҘ5)=0.1642, state whether X=5 is in the critical region.', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'P(XвүҘ5)=0.1642 > 0.10, so X=5 does NOT fall in the critical region. We need P(XвүҘc)вүӨ0.10 for c to be the critical value. Since P(XвүҘ5)>10%, we would not reject HвӮҖ for X=5.' },
      { q: 'Write out the four steps of a formal binomial hypothesis test.', marks: 4, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'Step 1: State HвӮҖ and HвӮҒ (with the value of p and direction of test).\nStep 2: State the significance level and test statistic distribution under HвӮҖ.\nStep 3: Calculate the p-value P(XвүҘobserved) or P(XвүӨobserved), or find the critical region.\nStep 4: Compare p-value to significance level (or check if X is in critical region) and write a conclusion in context.' },
      { q: 'In a hypothesis test, the actual significance level differs from the nominal significance level. Explain why this happens in binomial tests.', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'Because the binomial distribution is discrete, there may be no value c for which P(XвүӨc) equals exactly the nominal significance level (e.g. exactly 5%). The actual significance level is P(X is in the critical region), which may be less than 5%. The critical region is chosen to keep the actual significance level as close to (but not exceeding) the nominal level.' },
    ],
    amber: [
      { q: 'A medical treatment is known to be effective in 40% of cases. A researcher develops a new treatment and tests it on 20 patients. 11 recover.\n\nTest at the 5% significance level whether the new treatment is more effective.', marks: 6, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '\\(H_0:p=0.4\\) (same effectiveness as old treatment).\n\\(H_1:p>0.4\\) (new treatment is more effective).\n\nSignificance level: 5%. X~B(20,0.4) under HвӮҖ.\n\np-value = P(XвүҘ11) = 1вҲ’P(XвүӨ10) = 1вҲ’0.8725 = 0.1275.\n\n0.1275 > 0.05, so we do NOT reject HвӮҖ.\n\nConclusion: There is insufficient evidence at the 5% significance level to conclude that the new treatment is more effective than the original.' },
      { q: 'A manufacturer claims that 20% of their products are premium quality. A buyer suspects the proportion is lower. In a sample of 30 products, 3 are premium quality.\n\nTest at the 5% level whether the buyer\'s claim is supported.', marks: 6, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '\\(H_0:p=0.2\\), \\(H_1:p<0.2\\). X~B(30,0.2) under HвӮҖ.\n\np-value = P(XвүӨ3) = 0.1227.\n\n0.1227 > 0.05, so we do NOT reject HвӮҖ.\n\nConclusion: There is insufficient evidence at the 5% level to support the buyer\'s claim that fewer than 20% are premium quality.' },
      { q: 'A coin is tested for bias. It is flipped 25 times. Use a two-tailed test at 5% significance to test whether the coin is fair, given X = 17 heads.', marks: 6, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '\\(H_0:p=0.5\\), \\(H_1:p\\neq0.5\\). X~B(25,0.5) under HвӮҖ.\n\nFor a two-tailed test, use a 2.5% level in each tail.\nX=17 is in the upper tail. P(XвүҘ17)=1вҲ’P(XвүӨ16)=1вҲ’0.8654=0.1346.\n\n0.1346 > 0.025, so we do NOT reject HвӮҖ.\n\nConclusion: There is insufficient evidence at the 5% level to conclude the coin is biased.' },
      { q: 'Find the critical region for a test of \\(H_0:p=0.35\\), \\(H_1:p<0.35\\) at the 5% significance level, where \\(X\\sim B(20,0.35)\\). State the actual significance level.', marks: 5, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'Lower tail: need largest c such that P(XвүӨc)вүӨ0.05.\n\nP(XвүӨ3)=0.0453 вүӨ 0.05 вң“\nP(XвүӨ4)=0.1182 > 0.05 вң—\n\nCritical region: XвүӨ3.\n\nActual significance level = P(XвүӨ3) = 0.0453 = 4.53%.' },
      { q: 'A new drug is tested. Under standard conditions, 25% of patients improve. In a trial with 15 patients, 7 improve. Test at 1% significance whether the drug improves outcome.', marks: 6, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '\\(H_0:p=0.25\\), \\(H_1:p>0.25\\). X~B(15,0.25).\n\np-value = P(XвүҘ7) = 1вҲ’P(XвүӨ6) = 1вҲ’0.9434 = 0.0566.\n\n0.0566 > 0.01, so we do NOT reject HвӮҖ.\n\nConclusion: There is insufficient evidence at the 1% significance level to conclude that the drug increases the proportion of patients who improve.' },
      { q: 'Calculate the probability of a Type I error for the critical region XвүҘ7 when \\(X\\sim B(12,0.3)\\).', marks: 3, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'P(Type I error) = P(rejecting HвӮҖ | HвӮҖ is true) = P(XвүҘ7 | p=0.3).\n= 1вҲ’P(XвүӨ6) = 1вҲ’0.9614 = 0.0386 = 3.86%.\n\nThis is the actual significance level of the test.' },
      { q: 'A football player normally scores from 60% of penalty kicks. After a long injury absence, his manager believes the success rate has fallen. In the first 10 penalty kicks after return, he scores 4. Test at 5% significance.', marks: 6, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '\\(H_0:p=0.6\\), \\(H_1:p<0.6\\). X~B(10,0.6).\n\np-value = P(XвүӨ4) = 0.1662.\n\n0.1662 > 0.05, so we do NOT reject HвӮҖ.\n\nConclusion: There is insufficient evidence at the 5% significance level to conclude that the player\'s penalty success rate has fallen. The result could have occurred by chance.' },
      { q: 'Find the critical region for \\(H_0:p=0.5\\), \\(H_1:p\\neq0.5\\) with \\(X\\sim B(18,0.5)\\) at the 5% significance level. State the actual significance level.', marks: 5, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'Two-tailed: 2.5% in each tail.\n\nLower tail: P(XвүӨcвӮҒ)вүӨ0.025.\nP(XвүӨ5)=0.0481>0.025; P(XвүӨ4)=0.0154вүӨ0.025. Lower critical: XвүӨ4.\n\nUpper tail: P(XвүҘcвӮӮ)вүӨ0.025.\nP(XвүҘ13)=0.0481>0.025; P(XвүҘ14)=0.0154вүӨ0.025. Upper critical: XвүҘ14.\n\nCritical region: XвүӨ4 or XвүҘ14.\n\nActual significance level = P(XвүӨ4)+P(XвүҘ14) = 0.0154+0.0154 = 0.0308 = 3.08%.' },
      { q: 'In a hypothesis test, \\(H_0:p=0.4\\), \\(H_1:p\\neq0.4\\), n=20. The critical region is XвүӨ4 or XвүҘ13.\n(a) Find the probability of a Type I error.\n(b) Explain what a Type II error would mean in this context.', marks: 5, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '(a) P(Type I) = P(XвүӨ4 or XвүҘ13 | p=0.4) under B(20,0.4).\nP(XвүӨ4)=0.0510, P(XвүҘ13)=1вҲ’P(XвүӨ12)=1вҲ’0.9790=0.0210.\nP(Type I)=0.0510+0.0210=0.0720=7.2%.\n\n(b) A Type II error would be failing to reject HвӮҖ (concluding p=0.4) when in fact pвү 0.4 вҖ” i.e. the true probability is different from 0.4 but the test fails to detect this difference.' },
      { q: 'A cereal box claims it contains a prize in 1 in every 5 boxes. A child opens 20 boxes and finds only 1 prize. Test at 5% whether there is evidence the proportion of prize boxes is less than claimed.', marks: 6, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '\\(H_0:p=0.2\\), \\(H_1:p<0.2\\). X~B(20,0.2).\n\np-value = P(XвүӨ1).\nP(X=0)=(0.8)^{20}=0.01153\nP(X=1)=20(0.2)(0.8)^{19}=0.05765\nP(XвүӨ1)=0.06918.\n\n0.0692 > 0.05, so we do NOT reject HвӮҖ.\n\nConclusion: Insufficient evidence at 5% to conclude fewer than 20% of boxes contain prizes.' },
      { q: 'A quality inspector tests \\(H_0:p=0.1\\) (10% defective) against \\(H_1:p>0.1\\) at 5% significance, n=20. Find the critical region and state the actual significance level.', marks: 5, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'Upper tail: P(XвүҘc)вүӨ0.05, i.e. P(XвүӨcвҲ’1)вүҘ0.95.\nP(XвүӨ4)=0.9568вүҘ0.95. P(XвүӨ3)=0.8670<0.95.\nCritical region: XвүҘ5.\n\nActual significance level = P(XвүҘ5)=1вҲ’0.9568=0.0432=4.32%.' },
      { q: 'An election poll estimates 45% support Party A. A local survey of 25 people finds 16 support Party A. Test at 5% whether local support exceeds 45%.', marks: 6, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '\\(H_0:p=0.45\\), \\(H_1:p>0.45\\). X~B(25,0.45).\n\np-value = P(XвүҘ16)=1вҲ’P(XвүӨ15)=1вҲ’0.8173=0.1827.\n\n0.1827 > 0.05, so we do NOT reject HвӮҖ.\n\nConclusion: Insufficient evidence at 5% to conclude local support exceeds 45%.' },
      { q: 'For \\(H_0:p=0.6\\), \\(H_1:p<0.6\\), n=15, find the critical region at 10% significance and state the probability of Type I error.', marks: 5, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'Under B(15,0.6): need P(XвүӨc)вүӨ0.10.\nP(XвүӨ6)=0.0950вүӨ0.10 вң“\nP(XвүӨ7)=0.2131>0.10 вң—\nCritical region: XвүӨ6.\nP(Type I) = P(XвүӨ6 | p=0.6) = 0.0950 = 9.5%.' },
      { q: 'Explain why we use "p-value < significance level" to reject HвӮҖ, rather than "p-value > significance level".', marks: 3, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'The p-value measures how likely the observed data (or more extreme) is if HвӮҖ is true. A small p-value means the observed result is unlikely under HвӮҖ, giving evidence against it.\n\nIf p-value < Оұ, the observed result is unlikely enough (more extreme than the threshold) to be implausible under HвӮҖ, so we reject it.\n\nIf p-value > Оұ, the observed result is not sufficiently unusual under HвӮҖ, so we have no strong evidence to reject it.' },
      { q: 'A researcher tests whether a genetic trait occurs in more than 30% of offspring. In 20 offspring, 10 show the trait. Carry out a full hypothesis test at 5%.', marks: 6, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '\\(H_0:p=0.3\\), \\(H_1:p>0.3\\). X~B(20,0.3).\n\np-value = P(XвүҘ10) = 1вҲ’P(XвүӨ9) = 1вҲ’0.9520 = 0.0480.\n\n0.0480 < 0.05, so we REJECT HвӮҖ.\n\nConclusion: There is sufficient evidence at the 5% significance level to conclude that the proportion of offspring showing the trait is greater than 30%.' },
    ],
    red: [
      { q: 'Explain the difference between a one-tailed and a two-tailed test, and justify when each should be used. Give an example of each in the context of the binomial distribution.', marks: 7, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: 'One-tailed test: HвӮҒ specifies a direction of change (p>pвӮҖ or p<pвӮҖ). Use when prior theory or the research question specifies the direction of departure from HвӮҖ (e.g. a drug is expected to increase recovery rates вҖ” HвӮҒ:p>pвӮҖ).\n\nTwo-tailed test: HвӮҒ does not specify direction (pвү pвӮҖ). Use when any change from pвӮҖ is of interest and no prior direction is expected (e.g. testing whether a coin is biased in either direction вҖ” HвӮҒ:pвү 0.5).\n\nExample one-tailed: HвӮҖ:p=0.4 (proportion who pass), HвӮҒ:p>0.4 (new teaching method improves pass rate).\n\nExample two-tailed: HвӮҖ:p=0.5 (coin fair), HвӮҒ:pвү 0.5 (coin biased in either direction).\n\nThe two-tailed test splits significance level Оұ between both tails; the one-tailed test puts all Оұ in one tail, making it more powerful for detecting changes in the specified direction.' },
      { q: 'Find the two-tailed critical region for \\(H_0:p=0.3\\), \\(H_1:p\\neq0.3\\) at the 5% significance level with \\(X\\sim B(25,0.3)\\). State the actual significance level.', marks: 7, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: 'Two-tailed: 2.5% in each tail under B(25,0.3).\n\nLower tail: largest cвӮҒ with P(XвүӨcвӮҒ)вүӨ0.025.\nP(XвүӨ3)=0.0332>0.025; P(XвүӨ2)=0.0090вүӨ0.025. Lower critical: XвүӨ2.\n\nUpper tail: smallest cвӮӮ with P(XвүҘcвӮӮ)вүӨ0.025, i.e. P(XвүӨcвӮӮвҲ’1)вүҘ0.975.\nP(XвүӨ11)=0.9706вүҘ0.975; P(XвүӨ10)=0.9022<0.975. Upper critical: XвүҘ12.\n\nCritical region: XвүӨ2 or XвүҘ12.\n\nActual significance level = P(XвүӨ2)+P(XвүҘ12) = 0.0090+(1вҲ’0.9706) = 0.0090+0.0294 = 0.0384 = 3.84%.' },
      { q: 'A factory claims its machine produces 15% defective items. After a service, a quality engineer suspects the rate has changed. A sample of 30 items is inspected and 8 are defective.\n\nCarry out a full two-tailed hypothesis test at the 10% significance level.', marks: 8, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: '\\(H_0:p=0.15\\), \\(H_1:p\\neq0.15\\). X~B(30,0.15). Оұ=10%, so 5% in each tail.\n\nX=8 is in the upper tail. p-value (one side) = P(XвүҘ8)=1вҲ’P(XвүӨ7)=1вҲ’0.9302=0.0698.\n\nFor two-tailed: compare one-sided p-value with 5% (half the significance level).\n0.0698 > 0.05, so we do NOT reject HвӮҖ.\n\nConclusion: There is insufficient evidence at the 10% significance level to conclude that the defect rate has changed after the service.' },
      { q: 'Discuss Type I and Type II errors in the context of testing a new drug:\n\\(H_0\\): drug is no more effective than placebo (p=0.4).\n\\(H_1\\): drug is more effective (p>0.4).\n\nDescribe the consequences of each error type and explain the trade-off between them.', marks: 8, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: 'Type I error: Rejecting HвӮҖ when it is true вҖ” concluding the drug is more effective than placebo when it actually is not. Consequence: the drug may be approved and prescribed, wasting resources and potentially exposing patients to unnecessary side effects with no benefit. This is controlled by the significance level Оұ.\n\nType II error: Failing to reject HвӮҖ when HвӮҒ is true вҖ” concluding there is no evidence the drug works when it actually does. Consequence: an effective drug fails to reach patients who could benefit, and development is abandoned. Probability of Type II error = 1 вҲ’ power.\n\nTrade-off: Reducing Оұ (making the test stricter) decreases P(Type I) but increases P(Type II) вҖ” the test becomes less sensitive to a real effect. Reducing P(Type II) requires a larger sample size, which increases statistical power without inflating P(Type I).\n\nIn medicine, the consequences of each error must be weighed against each other when choosing Оұ.' },
      { q: 'A die is suspected of being biased. In 30 rolls, a 6 appears 9 times.\n\n(a) Carry out a one-tailed test at 5% to investigate whether the die is biased towards 6.\n(b) Find the critical region and state the actual significance level.\n(c) Would the conclusion change at the 1% significance level?', marks: 8, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: '(a) HвӮҖ: p=1/6, HвӮҒ: p>1/6. X~B(30, 1/6).\np-value = P(XвүҘ9) = 1вҲ’P(XвүӨ8).\nP(XвүӨ8) under B(30,1/6) = 0.9344 (calculator).\nP(XвүҘ9) = 0.0656.\n0.0656 > 0.05, so do NOT reject HвӮҖ.\nInsufficient evidence at 5% the die is biased towards 6.\n\n(b) Need P(XвүҘc)вүӨ0.05, i.e. P(XвүӨcвҲ’1)вүҘ0.95.\nP(XвүӨ8)=0.9344<0.95; P(XвүӨ9)=0.9699вүҘ0.95. Critical value c=10.\nCritical region: XвүҘ10.\nActual significance level = P(XвүҘ10) = 1вҲ’0.9699 = 0.0301 = 3.01%.\n\n(c) At 1%: P(XвүӨ10)=0.9699<0.99; P(XвүӨ11)=0.9876вүҘ0.99. Critical region XвүҘ12.\nSince X=9<12, we still do not reject HвӮҖ. Conclusion unchanged.' },
      { q: 'A market researcher tests whether more than half of consumers prefer Brand A over Brand B. In a survey of 20 consumers, 14 prefer Brand A.\n\n(a) Carry out a full hypothesis test at 5%.\n(b) Find the critical region at 5%.\n(c) Comment on the reliability of the test given that the sample size is only 20.', marks: 7, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: '(a) HвӮҖ: p=0.5, HвӮҒ: p>0.5. X~B(20,0.5).\np-value = P(XвүҘ14) = 1вҲ’P(XвүӨ13) = 1вҲ’0.9423 = 0.0577.\n0.0577 > 0.05. Do NOT reject HвӮҖ.\nInsufficient evidence at 5% to conclude more than half prefer Brand A.\n\n(b) Upper tail: need P(XвүҘc)вүӨ0.05.\nP(XвүҘ14)=0.0577>0.05; P(XвүҘ15)=0.0207вүӨ0.05. Critical region: XвүҘ15.\n\n(c) With n=20, the critical region only starts at X=15 (75%). This means the test has limited sensitivity вҖ” it can only detect a very large departure from p=0.5. A larger sample would give a more powerful test that could detect smaller differences. The test may miss genuinely higher preferences for Brand A (high Type II error probability).' },
      { q: 'Past data shows a genetics experiment produces 25% mutations. A new chemical is tested on 40 specimens; 4 mutations are observed.\n\nTest at 1% whether the chemical reduces the mutation rate.', marks: 7, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: 'HвӮҖ: p=0.25, HвӮҒ: p<0.25. X~B(40,0.25). Оұ=1%.\n\np-value = P(XвүӨ4).\nUsing calculator: P(XвүӨ4) = 0.0160.\n\n0.0160 > 0.01, so do NOT reject HвӮҖ.\n\nConclusion: There is insufficient evidence at the 1% significance level to conclude that the chemical reduces the mutation rate. (Just misses significance; would be rejected at 5%.)\n\nAlternatively find critical region: need P(XвүӨc)вүӨ0.01.\nP(XвүӨ3)=0.0049вүӨ0.01 вң“; P(XвүӨ4)=0.0160>0.01 вң—.\nCritical region: XвүӨ3. Since X=4>3, do not reject HвӮҖ. Same conclusion.' },
      { q: 'Design a hypothesis test at 5% significance for the following scenario:\n"A politician claims exactly 60% of voters support a policy. An opponent believes the true proportion is different."\n\nState HвӮҖ and HвӮҒ, describe the test, find the critical region for n=30, and explain what conclusion you would draw if X=25.', marks: 8, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: 'HвӮҖ: p=0.6 (politician is correct).\nHвӮҒ: pвү 0.6 (true proportion is different).\n\nTwo-tailed test at 5% significance. X~B(30,0.6). 2.5% in each tail.\n\nLower critical region: P(XвүӨcвӮҒ)вүӨ0.025.\nP(XвүӨ12)=0.0480>0.025; P(XвүӨ11)=0.0232вүӨ0.025. Lower: XвүӨ11.\n\nUpper critical region: P(XвүҘcвӮӮ)вүӨ0.025, P(XвүӨcвӮӮвҲ’1)вүҘ0.975.\nP(XвүӨ22)=0.9786вүҘ0.975; P(XвүӨ21)=0.9490<0.975. Upper: XвүҘ23.\n\nCritical region: XвүӨ11 or XвүҘ23.\n\nIf X=25: 25вүҘ23, so X=25 is in the critical region. Reject HвӮҖ.\n\nConclusion: There is sufficient evidence at the 5% level to conclude that the true proportion who support the policy differs from 60%.' },
      { q: 'For \\(X\\sim B(20,p)\\), the critical region for testing \\(H_0:p=0.5\\) at 5% two-tailed is XвүӨ5 or XвүҘ15.\n\n(a) Verify that the actual significance level is approximately 4.14%.\n(b) If the true value of p is 0.7, calculate P(Type II error).', marks: 8, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: '(a) Under B(20,0.5):\nP(XвүӨ5)=0.0207, P(XвүҘ15)=P(XвүӨ5)=0.0207 (by symmetry).\nActual Оұ = 0.0207+0.0207=0.0414=4.14%. вң“\n\n(b) P(Type II error) = P(not in critical region | p=0.7)\n= P(6вүӨXвүӨ14 | p=0.7)\n= P(XвүӨ14 | p=0.7)вҲ’P(XвүӨ5 | p=0.7).\n\nUnder B(20,0.7):\nP(XвүӨ14)=0.5836 (calculator).\nP(XвүӨ5)=0.0016.\nP(Type II) = 0.5836вҲ’0.0016 = 0.5820.\n\nSo if p=0.7, there is a 58.2% chance of failing to reject HвӮҖ вҖ” the test has low power for detecting p=0.7.' },
      { q: 'A genetic trait is carried by 35% of a species. A conservation biologist studying an isolated population observes 3 carriers in 20 specimens. Test at 5% whether the carrier rate in this population differs from the general rate.', marks: 7, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: 'HвӮҖ: p=0.35, HвӮҒ: pвү 0.35. X~B(20,0.35). Two-tailed test at 5%.\n\nX=3 is in the lower tail.\np-value (one side) = P(XвүӨ3) = 0.0444.\n\nFor two-tailed test, compare P(XвүӨ3) with 2.5% (half of 5%).\n0.0444 > 0.025, so do NOT reject HвӮҖ.\n\nConclusion: There is insufficient evidence at the 5% significance level to conclude that the carrier rate in this isolated population differs from 35%.\n\nNote: If a one-tailed test (p<0.35) had been used, p-value=0.0444<0.05 and HвӮҖ would have been rejected вҖ” illustrating that the choice of one-tailed vs two-tailed matters.' },
      { q: 'A teacher believes that less than half of students will pass without extra tuition. After extra tuition, 13 of 20 students pass. Conduct a full hypothesis test at 5% and discuss whether the result is practically significant as well as statistically significant.', marks: 7, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: 'HвӮҖ: p=0.5, HвӮҒ: p>0.5. X~B(20,0.5).\n\np-value = P(XвүҘ13) = 1вҲ’P(XвүӨ12) = 1вҲ’0.8684 = 0.1316.\n\n0.1316 > 0.05. Do NOT reject HвӮҖ.\n\nConclusion: Insufficient statistical evidence at 5% to conclude extra tuition increases the pass rate above 50%.\n\nPractical significance: X=13/20=65% pass rate is notably higher than the 50% baseline. However, with only n=20, the test has low statistical power вҖ” a larger sample would be needed to reliably detect a genuine increase from 50% to 65%. The result is potentially practically significant but statistical significance has not been established with this small sample. A larger study would be recommended before concluding the tuition is effective.' },
    ],
  },


  // в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җ
  // S6: Regression and Correlation
  // в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җ
  'S6': {
    name: 'Regression and Correlation',
    green: [
      { q: 'Describe the correlation shown by a PMCC of (a) r=0.92, (b) r=вҲ’0.15, (c) r=вҲ’0.88.', marks: 3, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: '(a) r=0.92: strong positive linear correlation. As one variable increases, the other tends to increase strongly.\n(b) r=вҲ’0.15: weak (negligible) negative correlation. Very little linear relationship.\n(c) r=вҲ’0.88: strong negative linear correlation. As one variable increases, the other tends to decrease strongly.' },
      { q: 'Explain what the PMCC measures and state its possible range of values.', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'The PMCC (Pearson product-moment correlation coefficient) r measures the strength and direction of the linear relationship between two variables. Its values range from вҲ’1 to +1 inclusive. r=1 is perfect positive linear correlation; r=вҲ’1 is perfect negative; r=0 indicates no linear correlation.' },
      { q: 'Given the regression line \\(\\hat{y}=3.2+0.85x\\), find the predicted value of y when x=10.', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: '\\(\\hat{y}=3.2+0.85(10)=3.2+8.5=11.7\\).' },
      { q: 'The regression line of y on x passes through the means: \\(\\bar{x}=5\\), \\(\\bar{y}=12\\). The gradient is 2.3. Find the equation of the regression line.', marks: 3, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'Using \\(\\hat{y}-\\bar{y}=b(x-\\bar{x})\\):\n\\(\\hat{y}-12=2.3(x-5)\\)\n\\(\\hat{y}=2.3x-11.5+12=2.3x+0.5\\)\nRegression line: \\(\\hat{y}=0.5+2.3x\\).' },
      { q: 'State what is meant by the <em>least squares regression line</em>.', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'The least squares regression line is the line that minimises the sum of the squares of the vertical residuals (the differences between observed y values and the fitted y values \\(\\hat{y}\\) on the line). It is the line of best fit that minimises \\(\\sum(y_i - \\hat{y}_i)^2\\).' },
      { q: 'State the formula for the gradient b of the regression line of y on x.', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: '\\(b=\\frac{S_{xy}}{S_{xx}}\\) where \\(S_{xy}=\\sum xy - \\frac{(\\sum x)(\\sum y)}{n}\\) and \\(S_{xx}=\\sum x^2 - \\frac{(\\sum x)^2}{n}\\).' },
      { q: 'A scatter diagram shows points closely clustered around a straight line with positive gradient. Describe the correlation and estimate r.', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'The scatter diagram shows strong positive linear correlation. The points are closely clustered around the line, suggesting r is close to +1, perhaps rвүҲ0.95 or higher.' },
      { q: 'The regression equation for predicting weight y (kg) from height x (cm) is \\(\\hat{y}=-60+0.7x\\). Interpret the gradient and intercept.', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'Gradient 0.7: for each additional centimetre of height, predicted weight increases by 0.7 kg.\nIntercept вҲ’60: this would predict a weight of вҲ’60 kg for zero height, which is meaningless in context. The intercept is the mathematical result of extending the line and should not be interpreted literally here.' },
      { q: 'Given \\(S_{xx}=120\\), \\(S_{xy}=84\\), \\(\\bar{x}=6\\), \\(\\bar{y}=14\\), find the regression line of y on x.', marks: 3, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: '\\(b=\\frac{S_{xy}}{S_{xx}}=\\frac{84}{120}=0.7\\).\n\\(a=\\bar{y}-b\\bar{x}=14-0.7(6)=14-4.2=9.8\\).\nRegression line: \\(\\hat{y}=9.8+0.7x\\).' },
      { q: 'Explain why the regression line of y on x should not be used to predict x from y.', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'The regression line of y on x is derived by minimising vertical distances (residuals in y). It minimises \\(\\sum(y_i-\\hat{y}_i)^2\\). Rearranging this line to give x from y does not give the regression line of x on y, which minimises horizontal distances. Using the y-on-x line to predict x gives biased estimates.' },
      { q: 'Data on advertising spend x (ВЈ000s) and sales y (ВЈ000s) gives: \\(n=8\\), \\(\\sum x=40\\), \\(\\sum y=160\\). Find \\(\\bar{x}\\) and \\(\\bar{y}\\).', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: '\\(\\bar{x}=40/8=5\\). \\(\\bar{y}=160/8=20\\).' },
      { q: 'Use the regression equation \\(\\hat{y}=4+1.5x\\) to predict y when x=8, and comment on the reliability of this prediction if the data range was 2вүӨxвүӨ7.', marks: 3, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: '\\(\\hat{y}=4+1.5(8)=4+12=16\\).\n\nReliability: x=8 is outside the data range (2 to 7), so this is extrapolation. The linear relationship may not hold beyond the observed range, so this prediction is unreliable.' },
      { q: 'State what a residual is in the context of linear regression.', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'A residual is the difference between an observed y value and the corresponding fitted value from the regression line: residual = \\(y_i - \\hat{y}_i\\). A positive residual means the observed point is above the line; a negative residual means it is below.' },
      { q: 'Two variables have PMCC r=0.3. Does this mean there is no relationship between them? Explain.', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'Not necessarily. r=0.3 indicates a weak positive linear relationship. However, a non-linear relationship (e.g. quadratic, exponential) could exist even though the linear correlation is low. The PMCC only measures the strength of linear association.' },
      { q: 'State the value of \\(r\\) for a scatter diagram where all points lie exactly on a straight line with negative gradient.', marks: 1, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: '\\(r=-1\\). When all points lie exactly on a straight line with negative gradient, there is perfect negative linear correlation.' },
    ],
    amber: [
      { q: 'The PMCC for a sample of n=18 pairs is r=0.52. Test at the 5% significance level whether there is a positive linear correlation between the two variables in the population.', marks: 5, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'HвӮҖ: ПҒ=0 (no linear correlation). HвӮҒ: ПҒ>0. One-tailed test, n=18, 5% level.\n\nCritical value from table: for n=18, 5% one-tailed, critical value=0.3973.\n\nSince r=0.52>0.3973, we reject HвӮҖ.\n\nConclusion: There is sufficient evidence at the 5% significance level of positive linear correlation between the two variables in the population.' },
      { q: 'The data is coded: \\(p=x-10\\), \\(q=\\frac{y}{2}\\). The regression line of q on p is \\(\\hat{q}=1.5+0.8p\\). Find the regression line of y on x.', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'Substituting back: \\(p=x-10\\) and \\(q=y/2\\).\n\\(y/2=1.5+0.8(x-10)\\)\n\\(y/2=1.5+0.8x-8=0.8x-6.5\\)\n\\(y=1.6x-13\\).\n\nRegression line of y on x: \\(\\hat{y}=-13+1.6x\\).' },
      { q: 'For 10 data pairs, the regression line of y on x is \\(\\hat{y}=20-2x\\). Explain what the gradient вҲ’2 tells you and discuss whether extrapolation to x=20 is reliable, given the data range is 2вүӨxвүӨ8.', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'Gradient вҲ’2: for each unit increase in x, y decreases by 2 on average.\n\nReliability: x=20 is far outside the data range (2 to 8). This is extrapolation. The linear relationship observed within the range may not hold at x=20 вҖ” the relationship could curve or change entirely. The prediction at x=20 is therefore unreliable and should not be used for decision-making.' },
      { q: 'For a dataset: \\(n=10\\), \\(S_{xx}=200\\), \\(S_{yy}=320\\), \\(S_{xy}=вҲ’160\\). Calculate r and interpret the result.', marks: 3, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '\\(r=\\frac{S_{xy}}{\\sqrt{S_{xx}S_{yy}}}=\\frac{-160}{\\sqrt{200\\times320}}=\\frac{-160}{\\sqrt{64000}}=\\frac{-160}{252.98}=-0.632\\).\n\nInterpretation: moderate negative linear correlation. As x increases, y tends to decrease, but the relationship is not particularly strong.' },
      { q: 'Carry out a two-tailed hypothesis test at 1% for zero population correlation, given r=0.71 and n=12.', marks: 5, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'HвӮҖ: ПҒ=0, HвӮҒ: ПҒвү 0. Two-tailed, n=12, 1% level.\n\nCritical value for n=12 at 1% two-tailed = 0.6614 (from table).\n\nSince |r|=0.71>0.6614, we reject HвӮҖ.\n\nConclusion: There is sufficient evidence at the 1% significance level to conclude that there is a non-zero linear correlation between the variables in the population.' },
      { q: 'Calculate \\(S_{xx}\\) and \\(S_{xy}\\) from the following summary statistics: \\(n=6\\), \\(\\sum x=30\\), \\(\\sum y=48\\), \\(\\sum x^2=180\\), \\(\\sum xy=260\\). Hence find the regression line of y on x.', marks: 5, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '\\(S_{xx}=\\sum x^2-\\frac{(\\sum x)^2}{n}=180-\\frac{900}{6}=180-150=30\\).\n\\(S_{xy}=\\sum xy-\\frac{(\\sum x)(\\sum y)}{n}=260-\\frac{30\\times48}{6}=260-240=20\\).\n\\(b=S_{xy}/S_{xx}=20/30=2/3\\).\n\\(\\bar{x}=30/6=5\\), \\(\\bar{y}=48/6=8\\).\n\\(a=8-(2/3)(5)=8-10/3=14/3\\approx4.67\\).\nRegression line: \\(\\hat{y}=\\frac{14}{3}+\\frac{2}{3}x\\).' },
      { q: 'The regression line of y on x is found from data within the range 5вүӨxвүӨ25. A student uses the line to predict y for x=50. State two reasons why this prediction may be unreliable.', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'Reason 1: x=50 is outside the data range (5 to 25). The regression line is only validated for values within this range. Extrapolating beyond the observed range assumes the linear trend continues, which may not be the case.\n\nReason 2: The relationship between the variables may be non-linear outside the observed range. The true relationship could curve or level off, making the linear model inappropriate for x=50.' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between <em>correlation</em> and <em>causation</em>. Give a realistic example where strong correlation does NOT imply causation.', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'Correlation: a statistical relationship between two variables вҖ” when one tends to change with the other.\nCausation: one variable directly causes changes in the other.\n\nStrong correlation does not imply causation because both variables may be driven by a third (confounding) variable, or the correlation may be coincidental.\n\nExample: There is a strong positive correlation between ice cream sales and drowning incidents. This does not mean ice cream causes drowning вҖ” both are caused by a third variable: hot weather (people eat ice cream and swim more when it is hot).' },
      { q: 'The regression line of sales y (thousands) on advertising spend x (ВЈhundreds) is \\(\\hat{y}=12+3.5x\\). Data range: 1вүӨxвүӨ8.\n(a) Predict sales when x=4.\n(b) Predict sales when x=15 and comment on reliability.', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '(a) \\(\\hat{y}=12+3.5(4)=12+14=26\\) thousand sales.\n\n(b) \\(\\hat{y}=12+3.5(15)=12+52.5=64.5\\) thousand sales.\nReliability: x=15 is well outside the data range (1 to 8). This is extrapolation вҖ” the linear relationship may not hold. The prediction of 64.5 thousand is unreliable.' },
      { q: 'For a bivariate dataset, r=вҲ’0.42 with n=25. Test at 5% two-tailed whether there is linear correlation in the population.', marks: 5, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'HвӮҖ: ПҒ=0, HвӮҒ: ПҒвү 0. n=25, two-tailed 5% level.\n\nCritical value for n=25 at 5% two-tailed = 0.3961.\n\nSince |r|=0.42>0.3961, we reject HвӮҖ.\n\nConclusion: There is sufficient evidence at the 5% level to conclude there is linear correlation between the variables in the population.' },
      { q: 'Explain why the PMCC can be misleading as a measure of association when the data contains an outlier. Suggest an alternative measure.', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'The PMCC measures linear association and uses all data points. A single outlier can dramatically increase or decrease r, making the correlation appear stronger or weaker than it truly is for the bulk of the data. For example, one extreme point could inflate r from 0.2 to 0.8.\n\nAlternative: Spearman\'s rank correlation coefficient is more robust to outliers because it only uses the ranks of the data values rather than their actual values. Outliers affect rank order less dramatically than they affect the calculated value of r.' },
      { q: 'The data is coded: \\(u=\\frac{x-50}{5}\\), \\(v=y-100\\). Summary gives: \\(S_{uu}=40\\), \\(S_{uv}=60\\), \\(\\bar{u}=2\\), \\(\\bar{v}=10\\).\nFind the regression line of y on x.', marks: 5, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '\\(b_{uv}=S_{uv}/S_{uu}=60/40=1.5\\).\n\\(a_{uv}=\\bar{v}-b_{uv}\\bar{u}=10-1.5(2)=7\\).\nRegression line of v on u: \\(\\hat{v}=7+1.5u\\).\n\nSubstitute \\(u=(x-50)/5\\) and \\(v=y-100\\):\n\\(y-100=7+1.5\\times\\frac{x-50}{5}=7+0.3(x-50)=7+0.3x-15=0.3x-8\\).\n\\(y=0.3x+92\\).\nRegression line: \\(\\hat{y}=92+0.3x\\).' },
      { q: 'State two assumptions that must be satisfied for the hypothesis test for zero population correlation coefficient ПҒ to be valid.', marks: 2, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '1. The data must be a random sample from a bivariate normal distribution (both variables are approximately normally distributed).\n2. The relationship between the variables should be linear (the PMCC only measures linear association).' },
      { q: 'Describe a scatter diagram. Given r=0.08, describe what the scatter diagram might look like and explain what this tells us.', marks: 3, tier: 'amber', diagram: true, modelAnswer: 'With r=0.08, the scatter diagram would show points scattered widely with no clear pattern вҖ” a random cloud of points with no discernible upward or downward trend. There might be very slight tendency for points to be higher on the right, but it would be barely perceptible.\n\nThis tells us there is virtually no linear correlation between the two variables. Changes in x are not associated with systematic changes in y. (A non-linear relationship could still exist.)' },
      { q: 'The summary statistics for 8 pairs are: \\(S_{xx}=64\\), \\(S_{yy}=100\\), \\(S_{xy}=48\\). Calculate r and test at 5% one-tailed (HвӮҒ:ПҒ>0).', marks: 5, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '\\(r=\\frac{48}{\\sqrt{64\\times100}}=\\frac{48}{80}=0.6\\).\n\nHвӮҖ: ПҒ=0, HвӮҒ: ПҒ>0. n=8, 5% one-tailed.\nCritical value for n=8 at 5% one-tailed = 0.6215.\n\n0.6 < 0.6215, so do NOT reject HвӮҖ.\n\nInsufficient evidence at 5% of positive linear correlation.' },
    ],
    red: [
      { q: 'Given raw data: (1,4), (2,7), (3,6), (4,9), (5,11).\n(a) Calculate \\(S_{xx}\\), \\(S_{xy}\\), and \\(r\\).\n(b) Find the regression line of y on x.\n(c) Interpret the gradient in context.', marks: 8, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: 'n=5. \\(\\sum x=15\\), \\(\\sum y=37\\), \\(\\sum x^2=55\\), \\(\\sum xy=125\\), \\(\\sum y^2=287\\).\n\n\\(S_{xx}=55-15^2/5=55-45=10\\).\n\\(S_{yy}=287-37^2/5=287-273.8=13.2\\).\n\\(S_{xy}=125-15\\times37/5=125-111=14\\).\n\n(a) \\(r=14/\\sqrt{10\\times13.2}=14/\\sqrt{132}=14/11.49=1.218\\)... Let me recalculate: \\(\\sqrt{132}\\approx11.49\\), r=14/11.49=1.218 вҖ” this exceeds 1 which is impossible. Recalculate \\(\\sum y^2\\): 16+49+36+81+121=303. \\(S_{yy}=303-37^2/5=303-273.8=29.2\\). r=14/\\(\\sqrt{10\\times29.2}\\)=14/\\(\\sqrt{292}\\)=14/17.09=0.819.\n\n(b) \\(b=14/10=1.4\\). \\(\\bar{x}=3\\), \\(\\bar{y}=37/5=7.4\\). \\(a=7.4-1.4(3)=7.4-4.2=3.2\\). Regression: \\(\\hat{y}=3.2+1.4x\\).\n\n(c) Gradient 1.4: for each unit increase in x, y increases by 1.4 on average.' },
      { q: 'The regression line of sales y (ВЈ000s) on temperature x (В°C) for an ice cream stall is \\(\\hat{y}=-8+2.5x\\), with r=0.94, data range 10вүӨxвүӨ30.\n\n(a) Predict sales when x=20.\n(b) Predict sales when x=5 and comment on reliability.\n(c) Does the high value of r prove that temperature causes increased sales? Explain.', marks: 7, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: '(a) \\(\\hat{y}=-8+2.5(20)=-8+50=42\\) (ВЈ42,000).\n\n(b) \\(\\hat{y}=-8+2.5(5)=-8+12.5=4.5\\) (ВЈ4,500). x=5 is outside the data range (10вҖ“30), so this is extrapolation. The linear model may not hold at lower temperatures вҖ” sales could behave differently below 10В°C. The prediction is unreliable.\n\n(c) No. Correlation does not imply causation. Even though r=0.94 shows a very strong positive linear relationship, this does not prove temperature causes sales. A third variable could explain both (e.g. seasonal tourism means more customers when warmer, and customers also buy more ice cream). A controlled experiment would be needed to establish causation.' },
      { q: 'Data on house size x (mВІ) and price y (ВЈ000s). The data is coded \\(u=x-100\\), \\(v=y-200\\).\nSummary: \\(n=10\\), \\(\\sum u=80\\), \\(\\sum v=120\\), \\(\\sum u^2=2880\\), \\(\\sum v^2=6100\\), \\(\\sum uv=3200\\).\n\n(a) Calculate \\(S_{uu}\\), \\(S_{vv}\\), \\(S_{uv}\\), and r.\n(b) Find the regression line of y on x.', marks: 8, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: '(a) \\(S_{uu}=2880-80^2/10=2880-640=2240\\).\n\\(S_{vv}=6100-120^2/10=6100-1440=4660\\).\n\\(S_{uv}=3200-80\\times120/10=3200-960=2240\\).\n\\(r=2240/\\sqrt{2240\\times4660}=2240/\\sqrt{10438400}=2240/3230.8=0.693\\).\n\n(b) \\(b_{uv}=S_{uv}/S_{uu}=2240/2240=1\\).\n\\(\\bar{u}=80/10=8\\), \\(\\bar{v}=120/10=12\\).\n\\(a_{uv}=12-1(8)=4\\). Regression: \\(\\hat{v}=4+u\\).\n\nSubstitute: \\(v=y-200\\), \\(u=x-100\\).\n\\(y-200=4+(x-100)=x-96\\).\n\\(y=x+104\\).\nRegression line: \\(\\hat{y}=104+x\\).' },
      { q: 'A scientist investigates the relationship between fertiliser dose x (g/mВІ) and crop yield y (kg/mВІ). Data: \\(S_{xx}=500\\), \\(S_{xy}=750\\), \\(S_{yy}=1200\\), \\(\\bar{x}=20\\), \\(\\bar{y}=15\\), \\(n=12\\).\n\n(a) Calculate r and the regression line.\n(b) Test at 1% whether ПҒ>0.\n(c) Predict yield when x=25.', marks: 8, tier: 'red', diagram: true, modelAnswer: '(a) \\(r=750/\\sqrt{500\\times1200}=750/\\sqrt{600000}=750/774.6=0.968\\).\n\\(b=750/500=1.5\\). \\(a=15-1.5(20)=15-30=-15\\).\nRegression: \\(\\hat{y}=-15+1.5x\\).\n\n(b) HвӮҖ:ПҒ=0, HвӮҒ:ПҒ>0. n=12, 1% one-tailed. Critical value=0.6339.\nSince r=0.968>0.6339, reject HвӮҖ. Strong evidence of positive linear correlation.\n\n(c) \\(\\hat{y}=-15+1.5(25)=-15+37.5=22.5\\) kg/mВІ. x=25 is near the data range (assume data is around 5вҖ“35), so this is reasonable interpolation. Prediction is reliable.' },
      { q: 'Explain the effect of an outlier on the PMCC and on the regression line. Use a specific example to illustrate your answer.', marks: 6, tier: 'red', diagram: true, modelAnswer: 'An outlier is a data point that does not follow the general pattern of the other data.\n\nEffect on PMCC: The PMCC uses each data point\'s deviation from the mean. An outlier creates a very large contribution to \\(S_{xy}\\) and \\(S_{xx}\\), potentially inflating or deflating r significantly. For example, if the general data gives rвүҲ0.3 (weak correlation) but one outlier is positioned far in the upper right, it could increase r to 0.7.\n\nEffect on regression line: The least squares regression line minimises \\(\\sum(y_i-\\hat{y}_i)^2\\). An outlier with a large residual contributes disproportionately (its squared residual is very large), pulling the regression line towards itself. The gradient and intercept can change substantially.\n\nExample: Plot showing 9 points with weak positive correlation; 1 extreme point. Without the outlier, rвүҲ0.3 and slope is near flat. With it, r jumps to 0.75 and slope increases. The regression line should be drawn with and without the outlier to show the effect.' },
      { q: 'A biologist measures the length x (mm) and weight y (mg) of 20 beetle specimens. The summary statistics are: \\(S_{xx}=180\\), \\(S_{xy}=270\\), \\(S_{yy}=450\\), \\(\\bar{x}=12\\), \\(\\bar{y}=18\\).\n\n(a) Find r and test at 5% two-tailed for non-zero ПҒ.\n(b) Find the regression line and predict weight for length=15 mm.', marks: 8, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: '(a) \\(r=270/\\sqrt{180\\times450}=270/\\sqrt{81000}=270/284.6=0.949\\).\n\nHвӮҖ:ПҒ=0, HвӮҒ:ПҒвү 0. n=20, 5% two-tailed. Critical value=0.4438.\n0.949>0.4438. Reject HвӮҖ. Strong evidence of linear correlation.\n\n(b) \\(b=270/180=1.5\\). \\(a=18-1.5(12)=18-18=0\\).\nRegression: \\(\\hat{y}=1.5x\\).\nPrediction: \\(\\hat{y}=1.5(15)=22.5\\) mg.' },
      { q: 'Describe carefully how you would carry out a hypothesis test for the population correlation coefficient ПҒ, including all the assumptions required. Apply your method for r=0.45, n=15, HвӮҒ:ПҒ>0 at 5%.', marks: 7, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: 'Method:\n1. State HвӮҖ:ПҒ=0 and HвӮҒ:ПҒ>0 (or вү 0 for two-tailed).\n2. Assume the data is a random sample from a bivariate normal distribution.\n3. State the significance level Оұ and whether the test is one- or two-tailed.\n4. Look up the critical value for the appropriate n and Оұ from the PMCC table.\n5. Compare |r| with the critical value.\n6. If |r|>critical value, reject HвӮҖ; otherwise do not reject.\n7. Write conclusion in context.\n\nApplication: HвӮҖ:ПҒ=0, HвӮҒ:ПҒ>0. n=15, 5% one-tailed. Critical value=0.4409.\nr=0.45>0.4409. Reject HвӮҖ.\nConclusion: There is sufficient evidence at the 5% level of positive linear correlation in the population.' },
      { q: 'Two datasets A and B both produce r=0.8. Dataset A has n=10; Dataset B has n=50. At 5% significance, test HвӮҖ:ПҒ=0 vs HвӮҒ:ПҒвү 0 for both. Compare the conclusions and explain why they differ.', marks: 7, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: 'HвӮҖ:ПҒ=0, HвӮҒ:ПҒвү 0. Two-tailed, 5%.\n\nDataset A (n=10): Critical value=0.6319. Since r=0.8>0.6319, reject HвӮҖ.\nDataset B (n=50): Critical value=0.2787. Since r=0.8>0.2787, reject HвӮҖ. Both reject.\n\nHowever, for Dataset A with n=10, a weaker r (e.g. r=0.5) would NOT be significant (0.5<0.6319). For Dataset B with n=50, even r=0.3 would be significant.\n\nReason for difference: With a larger sample, there is more evidence to detect smaller population correlations. With n=10, only strong correlations (r>0.63) can be detected at 5%. With n=50, even a modest correlation (r=0.28) is statistically detectable. This illustrates that statistical significance depends on both the size of the correlation and the sample size.' },
      { q: 'Discuss two limitations of linear regression as a statistical technique. For each limitation, describe a situation where the regression model would break down.', marks: 7, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: 'Limitation 1 вҖ” Linearity assumption: Linear regression assumes the relationship between x and y is linear. If the true relationship is non-linear (e.g. quadratic or exponential), the linear model will provide poor predictions and misleading gradient/intercept values. Situation: modelling population growth over time вҖ” populations grow exponentially, not linearly. The regression line would severely underestimate growth at large t.\n\nLimitation 2 вҖ” Extrapolation: The regression line is only valid within (or close to) the range of observed x values. Predictions outside this range (extrapolation) can be wildly inaccurate because the linear trend may not continue. Situation: modelling a child\'s height with age вҖ” the linear regression may fit well between ages 5 and 15, but extrapolating to age 30 would predict an implausibly tall adult since growth slows and stops.\n\n(Other valid limitations: outliers distorting the fit; not accounting for confounding variables; both variables must be measured without error.)\n' },
      { q: 'Interpret the following PMCC values in context and explain what conclusions (if any) can be drawn about causation:\n(a) r=0.99 between number of firefighters at a fire and property damage.\n(b) r=вҲ’0.85 between daily temperature and hot drink sales.\n(c) r=0.12 between shoe size and exam score.', marks: 6, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: '(a) r=0.99: very strong positive correlation between number of firefighters and damage. This does NOT mean more firefighters cause more damage. Larger fires require more firefighters AND cause more damage вҖ” fire size is the confounding variable. Correlation is explained by a lurking variable.\n\n(b) r=вҲ’0.85: strong negative correlation вҖ” as temperature increases, hot drink sales decrease. This is a plausible causal relationship (people prefer cold drinks in warm weather), but other factors (e.g. seasonal cafГ© pricing, outdoor seating availability) may also contribute. Causation is plausible but not proven by r alone.\n\n(c) r=0.12: very weak positive correlation вҖ” virtually no linear relationship between shoe size and exam score. No conclusions about causation can be drawn. This is likely a coincidental or spurious correlation with no causal mechanism.' },
    ],
  },


  // в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җ
  // S7: Conditional Probability
  // в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җ
  'S7': {
    name: 'Conditional Probability',
    green: [
      { q: 'State the formula for conditional probability \\(P(A|B)\\).', marks: 1, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: '\\(P(A|B) = \\frac{P(A \\cap B)}{P(B)}\\), provided \\(P(B) > 0\\).' },
      { q: '\\(P(A)=0.6\\), \\(P(B)=0.4\\), \\(P(A\\cap B)=0.24\\). Find \\(P(A|B)\\) and state whether A and B are independent.', marks: 3, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: '\\(P(A|B)=\\frac{0.24}{0.4}=0.6\\). Since \\(P(A|B)=P(A)=0.6\\), knowing B has occurred does not change the probability of A, so A and B ARE independent.' },
      { q: '\\(P(B)=0.5\\) and \\(P(A|B)=0.3\\). Find \\(P(A\\cap B)\\).', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: '\\(P(A\\cap B)=P(A|B)\\times P(B)=0.3\\times0.5=0.15\\).' },
      { q: 'Use the conditional probability formula to find \\(P(B|A)\\) given \\(P(A)=0.5\\), \\(P(B)=0.3\\), \\(P(A\\cap B)=0.15\\).', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: '\\(P(B|A)=\\frac{P(A\\cap B)}{P(A)}=\\frac{0.15}{0.5}=0.3\\). Note: since \\(P(B|A)=P(B)\\), A and B are independent.' },
      { q: 'Complete the probability tree for two events A and B: \\(P(A)=0.6\\), \\(P(B|A)=0.4\\), \\(P(B|A^\\prime)=0.7\\). Label all branches and find \\(P(B)\\).', marks: 4, tier: 'green', diagram: true, modelAnswer: 'First branch: A(0.6), AвҖІ(0.4).\nFrom A: B(0.4), BвҖІ(0.6). From AвҖІ: B(0.7), BвҖІ(0.3).\n\nP(B)=P(A)P(B|A)+P(AвҖІ)P(B|AвҖІ)=0.6(0.4)+0.4(0.7)=0.24+0.28=0.52.' },
      { q: 'State what it means for event A to be independent of event B, using conditional probability.', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'A is independent of B if \\(P(A|B)=P(A)\\), meaning that knowing B has occurred does not change the probability of A. Equivalently, \\(P(A\\cap B)=P(A)\\times P(B)\\).' },
      { q: 'A survey shows 40% of people are vegetarian (V) and 30% exercise regularly (E). 15% are both vegetarian and exercise regularly. Find \\(P(V|E)\\).', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: '\\(P(V|E)=\\frac{P(V\\cap E)}{P(E)}=\\frac{0.15}{0.30}=0.5\\). Given that a person exercises regularly, the probability they are vegetarian is 0.5.' },
      { q: 'Use a tree diagram to find \\(P(A^\\prime \\cap B)\\) given \\(P(A)=0.7\\), \\(P(B|A)=0.2\\), \\(P(B|A^\\prime)=0.6\\).', marks: 3, tier: 'green', diagram: true, modelAnswer: 'Tree: A(0.7)вҶ’B(0.2), BвҖІ(0.8); AвҖІ(0.3)вҶ’B(0.6), BвҖІ(0.4).\n\\(P(A^\\prime\\cap B)=P(A^\\prime)\\times P(B|A^\\prime)=0.3\\times0.6=0.18\\).' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between \\(P(A|B)\\) and \\(P(B|A)\\). Give a real-world example where they are clearly different.', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: '\\(P(A|B)\\): probability of A given B has already occurred. \\(P(B|A)\\): probability of B given A has already occurred. These are generally different.\n\nExample: P(smoker | lung cancer)вүҲ0.85 (most lung cancer patients smoked), but P(lung cancer | smoker)вүҲ0.15 (only a minority of smokers get lung cancer). Clearly different values.' },
      { q: 'From a table: 60 boys, 40 girls. 24 boys and 16 girls play football. A student is chosen at random and plays football. Find the probability the student is a girl.', marks: 3, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'Total football players = 24+16=40. P(girl|plays football)=16/40=0.4.' },
      { q: 'A bag has 3 red and 5 blue balls. One is drawn and not replaced. Find P(second is red | first is red).', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'After removing 1 red, 2 red and 5 blue remain (7 total). P(2nd red | 1st red) = 2/7.' },
      { q: '\\(P(A|B)=0.4\\), \\(P(B)=0.25\\). Find \\(P(A\\cap B)\\).', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: '\\(P(A\\cap B)=P(A|B)\\times P(B)=0.4\\times0.25=0.1\\).' },
      { q: 'Two events A and B: \\(P(A)=0.5\\), \\(P(B)=0.3\\), and they are independent. Find \\(P(A|B^\\prime)\\).', marks: 3, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'Since A and B are independent, A and BвҖІ are also independent (proved in S3). Therefore \\(P(A|B^\\prime)=P(A)=0.5\\).' },
      { q: 'State the law of total probability for events A and B.', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: '\\(P(B)=P(B|A)P(A)+P(B|A^\\prime)P(A^\\prime)\\). This says the total probability of B is the weighted sum of its probability given A and given not-A, weighted by the probabilities of A and AвҖІ.' },
      { q: 'A test for a disease has P(positive|disease)=0.9 and P(positive|no disease)=0.05. P(disease)=0.1. Find P(positive test).', marks: 3, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'P(positive) = P(+|D)P(D)+P(+|DвҖІ)P(DвҖІ) = 0.9(0.1)+0.05(0.9) = 0.09+0.045 = 0.135.' },
    ],
    amber: [
      { q: 'Box 1 has 3 red, 2 blue. Box 2 has 1 red, 4 blue. A box is chosen with equal probability, then a ball drawn. Find P(red ball).', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'P(red) = P(B1)P(R|B1)+P(B2)P(R|B2) = 0.5Г—(3/5)+0.5Г—(1/5) = 0.3+0.1 = 0.4.' },
      { q: 'Disease prevalence 1%. Test sensitivity P(+|D)=0.95, specificity P(вҲ’|DвҖІ)=0.98. Find P(D|+) using Bayes\' theorem.', marks: 6, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'P(D)=0.01, P(DвҖІ)=0.99.\nP(+|D)=0.95, P(+|DвҖІ)=0.02 (since specificity=0.98).\nP(+)=0.95(0.01)+0.02(0.99)=0.0095+0.0198=0.0293.\nP(D|+)=P(+|D)P(D)/P(+)=0.0095/0.0293вүҲ0.324.\nOnly about 32.4% of positive tests indicate true disease.' },
      { q: 'Three events A, B, C with three-circle Venn diagram: P(A)=0.5, P(B)=0.4, P(C)=0.3, P(AвҲ©B)=0.2, P(AвҲ©C)=0.15, P(BвҲ©C)=0.1, P(AвҲ©BвҲ©C)=0.05.\nFind P(B|A) and P(A|BвҲ©C).', marks: 5, tier: 'amber', diagram: true, modelAnswer: 'P(B|A)=P(AвҲ©B)/P(A)=0.20/0.50=0.4.\nP(BвҲ©C)=0.1. P(AвҲ©BвҲ©C)=0.05.\nP(A|BвҲ©C)=P(AвҲ©BвҲ©C)/P(BвҲ©C)=0.05/0.10=0.5.' },
      { q: 'From a contingency table:\n\n|  | Like | Dislike | Total |\n|-----|------|---------|-------|\n| Male | 35 | 15 | 50 |\n| Female | 20 | 30 | 50 |\n| Total | 55 | 45 | 100 |\n\n(a) Find P(like|female). (b) Find P(male|dislike). (c) Are gender and preference independent?', marks: 5, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '(a) P(like|female)=20/50=0.4.\n(b) P(male|dislike)=15/45=1/3вүҲ0.333.\n(c) P(like)=55/100=0.55. P(like|male)=35/50=0.7вү 0.55. NOT independent.' },
      { q: 'A factory has two machines. Machine A produces 70% of items, 4% defective. Machine B produces 30%, 6% defective. Given an item is defective, find P(from Machine A).', marks: 5, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'P(D)=0.7(0.04)+0.3(0.06)=0.028+0.018=0.046.\nP(A|D)=P(D|A)P(A)/P(D)=0.028/0.046вүҲ0.609.\nAbout 60.9% of defective items come from Machine A.' },
      { q: 'Events A and B: P(A)=0.4, P(B)=0.5, P(AвҲӘB)=0.7. Find P(A|B) and P(B|A). Test independence.', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'P(AвҲ©B)=0.4+0.5-0.7=0.2.\nP(A|B)=0.2/0.5=0.4. P(B|A)=0.2/0.4=0.5.\nSince P(A|B)=P(A)=0.4 and P(B|A)=P(B)=0.5, A and B ARE independent.' },
      { q: 'A student passes maths (M) with P=0.7. Given they pass maths, P(pass science|pass maths)=0.8. Given they fail maths, P(pass science|fail maths)=0.5. Find P(pass science) and P(pass maths | pass science).', marks: 5, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'P(pass science)=0.7(0.8)+0.3(0.5)=0.56+0.15=0.71.\nP(M|pass sci)=P(pass sci|M)P(M)/P(pass sci)=0.56/0.71вүҲ0.789.' },
      { q: 'A bag contains 4 red and 6 blue balls. Two balls are drawn without replacement. Given the second is red, find P(first is blue).', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'P(first B, second R)=6/10 Г— 4/9=24/90.\nP(second R)=P(R first)P(R second|R first)+P(B first)P(R second|B first)=4/10Г—3/9+6/10Г—4/9=12/90+24/90=36/90.\nP(first B | second R)=(24/90)/(36/90)=24/36=2/3.' },
      { q: 'Apply the law of total probability: P(A)=0.3, P(B|A)=0.6, P(B|AвҖІ)=0.2. Find P(A|B).', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'P(B)=0.3(0.6)+0.7(0.2)=0.18+0.14=0.32.\nP(A|B)=P(B|A)P(A)/P(B)=0.18/0.32=0.5625.' },
      { q: 'Three machines X, Y, Z produce 50%, 30%, 20% of a factory\'s output. Defect rates: X=2%, Y=5%, Z=4%. An item is found defective. Find P(from Y|defective).', marks: 5, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'P(D)=0.5(0.02)+0.3(0.05)+0.2(0.04)=0.010+0.015+0.008=0.033.\nP(Y|D)=0.015/0.033вүҲ0.455.' },
      { q: 'A probability tree for a two-stage experiment. First stage: P(A)=0.4, P(AвҖІ)=0.6. Given A: P(B|A)=0.3. Given AвҖІ: P(B|AвҖІ)=0.7. Complete the tree and find P(A|B).', marks: 5, tier: 'amber', diagram: true, modelAnswer: 'Tree: A(0.4)вҶ’B(0.3),BвҖІ(0.7); AвҖІ(0.6)вҶ’B(0.7),BвҖІ(0.3).\nP(AвҲ©B)=0.4(0.3)=0.12. P(AвҖІвҲ©B)=0.6(0.7)=0.42.\nP(B)=0.12+0.42=0.54.\nP(A|B)=0.12/0.54=2/9вүҲ0.222.' },
      { q: 'A fair die is rolled. Let A={score вүҘ 4} and B={score is even}. Find P(A|B) and P(B|A).', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'A={4,5,6}, B={2,4,6}. AвҲ©B={4,6}.\nP(A|B)=P(AвҲ©B)/P(B)=(2/6)/(3/6)=2/3.\nP(B|A)=P(AвҲ©B)/P(A)=(2/6)/(3/6)=2/3.' },
      { q: 'A class: 60% boys, 40% girls. 70% of boys wear glasses, 50% of girls wear glasses. A student is chosen and wears glasses. Find P(boy|wears glasses).', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'P(glasses)=0.6(0.7)+0.4(0.5)=0.42+0.20=0.62.\nP(boy|glasses)=0.42/0.62=21/31вүҲ0.677.' },
      { q: 'Using a Venn diagram, find P(A|BвҖІ) given P(A)=0.6, P(B)=0.4, P(AвҲ©B)=0.25.', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', diagram: true, modelAnswer: 'P(AвҲ©BвҖІ)=P(A)-P(AвҲ©B)=0.6-0.25=0.35.\nP(BвҖІ)=1-0.4=0.6.\nP(A|BвҖІ)=P(AвҲ©BвҖІ)/P(BвҖІ)=0.35/0.6=7/12вүҲ0.583.\n\nVenn diagram: only A region = 0.35, AвҲ©B = 0.25, only B = 0.15, neither = 0.25.' },
      { q: 'Two cards are drawn without replacement from 52 cards. Find (a) P(both aces), (b) P(second ace | first ace).', marks: 3, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: '(b) After drawing 1 ace, 3 aces remain from 51 cards. P(second ace|first ace)=3/51=1/17.\n(a) P(both aces)=P(first ace)Г—P(second|first)=4/52Г—3/51=12/2652=1/221.' },
    ],
    red: [
      { q: 'A disease affects 2% of a population. A test has sensitivity 0.98 (P(+|D)) and specificity 0.95 (P(вҲ’|DвҖІ)).\n(a) Draw a tree diagram.\n(b) Find P(positive test).\n(c) Find P(D|+) вҖ” the positive predictive value.\n(d) Comment on the usefulness of the test given its high sensitivity.', marks: 8, tier: 'red', diagram: true, modelAnswer: '(a) Tree: D(0.02)вҶ’+(0.98),вҲ’(0.02); DвҖІ(0.98)вҶ’+(0.05),вҲ’(0.95).\n\n(b) P(+)=0.02(0.98)+0.98(0.05)=0.0196+0.0490=0.0686.\n\n(c) P(D|+)=P(+|D)P(D)/P(+)=0.0196/0.0686вүҲ0.286.\n\n(d) Despite 98% sensitivity, only 28.6% of positive tests are true positives. This is because the disease is rare (2% prevalence) вҖ” the large number of disease-free people generates many false positives (0.05Г—0.98вүҲ4.9% of the population) which swamp the true positives. High sensitivity alone is insufficient for screening rare diseases; high specificity is equally important.' },
      { q: 'Apply Bayes\' theorem formally to the following: A factory has three suppliers, X (P=0.5), Y (P=0.3), Z (P=0.2). Component failure rates: X=3%, Y=7%, Z=5%. A component fails. Find P(from supplier Y | failed).', marks: 7, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: 'P(fail)=P(F|X)P(X)+P(F|Y)P(Y)+P(F|Z)P(Z)\n=0.03(0.5)+0.07(0.3)+0.05(0.2)\n=0.015+0.021+0.010=0.046.\n\nP(Y|fail)=P(F|Y)P(Y)/P(fail)=0.021/0.046вүҲ0.457.\n\nGiven a component has failed, there is approximately a 45.7% probability it came from supplier Y.' },
      { q: 'A and B are events. P(A)=0.35, P(B)=0.6, P(A|B)=0.4.\n(a) Find P(AвҲ©B).\n(b) Find P(AвҲӘB).\n(c) Find P(B|A).\n(d) Find P(A|BвҖІ).\n(e) Are A and B independent?', marks: 8, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: '(a) P(AвҲ©B)=P(A|B)Г—P(B)=0.4Г—0.6=0.24.\n\n(b) P(AвҲӘB)=0.35+0.6-0.24=0.71.\n\n(c) P(B|A)=P(AвҲ©B)/P(A)=0.24/0.35=24/35вүҲ0.686.\n\n(d) P(AвҲ©BвҖІ)=P(A)-P(AвҲ©B)=0.35-0.24=0.11. P(BвҖІ)=0.4. P(A|BвҖІ)=0.11/0.4=0.275.\n\n(e) For independence: P(A|B)=P(A)? 0.4вү 0.35. NOT independent.' },
      { q: 'A quality control problem: 60% of items from line 1, 40% from line 2. Line 1: 2% substandard. Line 2: 5% substandard.\n(a) Find P(substandard).\n(b) An item is substandard. Find P(line 1|substandard) and P(line 2|substandard).\n(c) If the process on line 2 is improved so its defect rate falls to 2%, find the new P(substandard) and P(line 2|substandard).', marks: 8, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: '(a) P(sub)=0.6(0.02)+0.4(0.05)=0.012+0.020=0.032.\n\n(b) P(L1|sub)=0.012/0.032=0.375. P(L2|sub)=0.020/0.032=0.625.\n\n(c) New P(sub)=0.6(0.02)+0.4(0.02)=0.012+0.008=0.020.\nNew P(L2|sub)=0.008/0.020=0.40.\nThe proportion of substandard items from line 2 drops from 62.5% to 40% after the improvement.' },
      { q: 'A hospital tests patients for two conditions, A and B. P(A)=0.3, P(B)=0.25. Given a patient has condition A, P(B|A)=0.4.\n(a) Find P(AвҲ©B).\n(b) Draw a Venn diagram.\n(c) Find P(AвҲӘB).\n(d) Find P(A|B).\n(e) Explain whether conditions A and B are independent.', marks: 8, tier: 'red', diagram: true, modelAnswer: '(a) P(AвҲ©B)=P(B|A)Г—P(A)=0.4Г—0.3=0.12.\n\n(b) Draw overlapping circles. Only A: 0.18; AвҲ©B: 0.12; Only B: 0.13; Neither: 0.57.\n\n(c) P(AвҲӘB)=0.3+0.25-0.12=0.43.\n\n(d) P(A|B)=0.12/0.25=0.48.\n\n(e) For independence: P(A|B)=P(A)? 0.48вү 0.30. Also P(AвҲ©B)=0.12вү P(A)P(B)=0.075. NOT independent. Having condition A makes condition B more likely вҖ” the conditions are positively associated.' },
      { q: 'Design a probability experiment involving conditional probability to model the following:\n\n"A biased coin has P(H)=0.6. If heads, a red die is rolled; if tails, a blue die is rolled. The red die has P(six)=1/3, the blue die has P(six)=1/6."\n\n(a) Draw a complete tree diagram.\n(b) Find P(six).\n(c) Find P(heads|six).\n(d) Find P(tails|not six).', marks: 8, tier: 'red', diagram: true, modelAnswer: '(a) Tree: H(0.6)вҶ’six(1/3),not six(2/3); T(0.4)вҶ’six(1/6),not six(5/6).\n\n(b) P(six)=0.6(1/3)+0.4(1/6)=0.2+1/15=0.2+0.0667=0.2667.\n\n(c) P(H|six)=P(six|H)P(H)/P(six)=0.6(1/3)/0.2667=0.2/0.2667=0.75.\n\n(d) P(not six)=1-0.2667=0.7333.\nP(TвҲ©not six)=0.4Г—5/6=0.3333.\nP(T|not six)=0.3333/0.7333вүҲ0.455.' },
      { q: 'Two independent events A and B each have probability p. Find P(AвҲӘB) and P(A|AвҲӘB) in terms of p. Evaluate for p=0.4.', marks: 7, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: 'P(AвҲӘB)=P(A)+P(B)-P(A)P(B)=p+p-pВІ=2p-pВІ=p(2-p).\n\nP(AвҲ©(AвҲӘB))=P(A) (since A is a subset of AвҲӘB).\nP(A|AвҲӘB)=P(A)/P(AвҲӘB)=p/(2p-pВІ)=1/(2-p).\n\nFor p=0.4:\nP(AвҲӘB)=0.4(1.6)=0.64.\nP(A|AвҲӘB)=0.4/0.64=1/1.6=0.625.' },
      { q: 'A criminal tribunal uses probability. P(guilty)=0.7 (prior). Evidence E is found: P(E|guilty)=0.9, P(E|innocent)=0.2. Find the posterior P(guilty|evidence) using Bayes\' theorem. Discuss the implication.', marks: 7, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: 'Prior: P(G)=0.7, P(I)=0.3.\nP(E|G)=0.9, P(E|I)=0.2.\n\nP(E)=P(E|G)P(G)+P(E|I)P(I)=0.9(0.7)+0.2(0.3)=0.63+0.06=0.69.\n\nP(G|E)=P(E|G)P(G)/P(E)=0.63/0.69вүҲ0.913.\n\nDiscussion: The evidence increases the probability of guilt from 70% to 91.3%. This illustrates how evidence updates prior beliefs. However, the result is very sensitive to the choice of prior (0.7) вҖ” a different prior would give a different posterior. In legal contexts, Bayes\' theorem must be applied carefully; the court should be cautious about stating a probability of guilt, as this could be misinterpreted.' },
      { q: 'Three events A, B, C are mutually independent, each with probability 1/2. Find:\n(a) P(AвҲ©BвҲ©C)\n(b) P(exactly one of A, B, C occurs)\n(c) P(A|BвҲӘC)', marks: 8, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: '(a) P(AвҲ©BвҲ©C)=(1/2)^3=1/8.\n\n(b) Exactly one occurs:\nP(A only)=P(A)P(BвҖІ)P(CвҖІ)=(1/2)^3=1/8.\nBy symmetry, P(B only)=P(C only)=1/8.\nP(exactly one)=3/8.\n\n(c) P(AвҲ©(BвҲӘC))=P(AвҲ©B)+P(AвҲ©C)-P(AвҲ©BвҲ©C)=(1/4)+(1/4)-(1/8)=3/8.\nP(BвҲӘC)=P(B)+P(C)-P(BвҲ©C)=1/2+1/2-1/4=3/4.\nP(A|BвҲӘC)=(3/8)/(3/4)=1/2=P(A).\nSince P(A|BвҲӘC)=P(A), A is independent of BвҲӘC.' },
      { q: 'A diagnostic company offers two successive tests T1 and T2. P(disease)=0.05. T1: P(+|D)=0.90, P(вҲ’|DвҖІ)=0.95. Only patients positive on T1 take T2: P(+|D)=0.95, P(+|DвҖІ)=0.02.\n\nFind P(both tests positive | disease) and P(D | both positive).', marks: 8, tier: 'red', diagram: true, modelAnswer: 'Step 1: P(T1+) = 0.90(0.05)+0.05(0.95)=0.045+0.0475=0.0925.\n\nAmong T1+ patients:\nP(D|T1+)=P(T1+|D)P(D)/P(T1+)=0.045/0.0925=0.4865.\nP(DвҖІ|T1+)=1-0.4865=0.5135.\n\nStep 2 (among T1+ patients):\nP(T2+|T1+)=P(T2+|DвҲ©T1+)P(D|T1+)+P(T2+|DвҖІвҲ©T1+)P(DвҖІ|T1+)\n=0.95(0.4865)+0.02(0.5135)=0.4622+0.01027=0.4724.\n\nP(D|both+)=0.95Г—0.4865/0.4724=0.4622/0.4724вүҲ0.978.\n\nConclusion: Two positive tests raise the probability of disease from 5% to ~97.8%, showing how successive testing drastically improves diagnostic certainty.' },
      { q: 'A drawer contains 3 red, 4 green, and 5 blue socks. Two socks are drawn without replacement.\n(a) Draw a complete tree diagram showing all colour combinations.\n(b) Find P(both socks same colour).\n(c) Find P(first red | second blue).\n(d) Find P(at least one green).', marks: 8, tier: 'red', diagram: true, modelAnswer: 'Total = 12 socks.\n\n(a) First draw: P(R)=3/12, P(G)=4/12, P(B)=5/12. For each, second draw probabilities adjust for the removed sock.\n\n(b) P(RR)=3/12Г—2/11=6/132. P(GG)=4/12Г—3/11=12/132. P(BB)=5/12Г—4/11=20/132.\nP(same)=38/132=19/66.\n\n(c) P(second blue)=P(R first)P(B|R)+P(G first)P(B|G)+P(B first)P(B|B)\n=3/12Г—5/11+4/12Г—5/11+5/12Г—4/11=15/132+20/132+20/132=55/132=5/12.\nP(first R вҲ© second B)=3/12Г—5/11=15/132.\nP(first R|second B)=15/132Г·55/132=15/55=3/11.\n\n(d) P(at least one green)=1-P(no green)=1-P(R or B first)P(R or B second given first not green).\nP(no green)=8/12Г—7/11=56/132=14/33.\nP(at least one green)=1-14/33=19/33.' },
    ],
  },


  // в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җ
  // S8: Normal Distribution
  // в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җ
  'S8': {
    name: 'Normal Distribution',
    green: [
      { q: 'State the notation for a normal distribution with mean 50 and standard deviation 8, and sketch its shape.', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: '\\(X\\sim N(50, 8^2)\\) or equivalently \\(N(50, 64)\\). The distribution is bell-shaped (symmetric), centred at 50, with the curve tailing off on both sides. About 95% of values lie within 2 standard deviations of the mean (between 34 and 66).' },
      { q: '\\(X\\sim N(40,25)\\). Find \\(P(X<45)\\).', marks: 3, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'Standardise: \\(Z=\\frac{X-\\mu}{\\sigma}=\\frac{45-40}{5}=1\\).\n\\(P(X<45)=P(Z<1)=0.8413\\) (from standard normal tables).' },
      { q: '\\(X\\sim N(60,16)\\). Find \\(P(X>64)\\).', marks: 3, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: '\\(\\sigma=4\\). \\(Z=\\frac{64-60}{4}=1\\).\n\\(P(X>64)=P(Z>1)=1-P(Z<1)=1-0.8413=0.1587\\).' },
      { q: '\\(X\\sim N(100,225)\\). Find \\(P(85<X<115)\\).', marks: 4, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: '\\(\\sigma=15\\).\n\\(Z_1=\\frac{85-100}{15}=-1\\), \\(Z_2=\\frac{115-100}{15}=1\\).\n\\(P(-1<Z<1)=P(Z<1)-P(Z<-1)=0.8413-(1-0.8413)=0.8413-0.1587=0.6826\\).' },
      { q: '\\(X\\sim N(30,9)\\). Find \\(x\\) such that \\(P(X<x)=0.9\\).', marks: 3, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: '\\(\\sigma=3\\). From tables, \\(P(Z<z)=0.9\\) gives \\(z=1.282\\).\n\\(x=\\mu+z\\sigma=30+1.282\\times3=30+3.846=33.85\\) (to 4 s.f.).' },
      { q: '\\(X\\sim N(50,100)\\). Find \\(P(X<38)\\).', marks: 3, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: '\\(\\sigma=10\\). \\(Z=\\frac{38-50}{10}=-1.2\\).\n\\(P(X<38)=P(Z<-1.2)=1-P(Z<1.2)=1-0.8849=0.1151\\).' },
      { q: 'State two properties of the standard normal distribution \\(Z\\sim N(0,1)\\).', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: '1. Mean = 0 and standard deviation = 1 (variance = 1).\n2. The distribution is symmetric about 0: P(Z<вҲ’z)=P(Z>z)=1вҲ’P(Z<z).' },
      { q: '\\(X\\sim N(\\mu,\\sigma^2)\\). The standardisation formula is \\(Z=\\frac{X-\\mu}{\\sigma}\\). Use this to explain what standardising achieves.', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'Standardising converts any normal distribution \\(N(\\mu,\\sigma^2)\\) into the standard normal \\(Z\\sim N(0,1)\\). It measures how many standard deviations x is above or below the mean. This allows us to use a single set of standard normal tables regardless of the original values of Ој and Пғ.' },
      { q: '\\(X\\sim N(20,16)\\). Find \\(P(X>25)\\).', marks: 3, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: '\\(\\sigma=4\\). \\(Z=\\frac{25-20}{4}=1.25\\).\n\\(P(X>25)=P(Z>1.25)=1-0.8944=0.1056\\).' },
      { q: '\\(X\\sim N(45,36)\\). Find \\(P(39<X<51)\\).', marks: 4, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: '\\(\\sigma=6\\).\n\\(Z_1=\\frac{39-45}{6}=-1\\), \\(Z_2=\\frac{51-45}{6}=1\\).\n\\(P(-1<Z<1)=0.8413-0.1587=0.6826\\).' },
      { q: '\\(X\\sim N(0,1)\\). Use symmetry to find \\(P(Z>1.5)\\) given \\(P(Z<1.5)=0.9332\\).', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: '\\(P(Z>1.5)=1-P(Z<1.5)=1-0.9332=0.0668\\).\nAlternatively, by symmetry: \\(P(Z>1.5)=P(Z<-1.5)=0.0668\\).' },
      { q: '\\(X\\sim N(\\mu, 4)\\). Given \\(P(X<12)=0.9772\\), find \\(\\mu\\).', marks: 3, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: '\\(\\sigma=2\\). \\(P(Z<z)=0.9772\\) gives \\(z=2\\).\n\\(\\frac{12-\\mu}{2}=2 \\Rightarrow 12-\\mu=4 \\Rightarrow \\mu=8\\).' },
      { q: '\\(X\\sim N(50,\\sigma^2)\\). Given \\(P(X<56)=0.8413\\), find \\(\\sigma\\).', marks: 3, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: '\\(P(Z<1)=0.8413\\), so \\(z=1\\).\n\\(\\frac{56-50}{\\sigma}=1 \\Rightarrow \\sigma=6\\).' },
      { q: '\\(X\\sim N(75,100)\\). Find \\(x\\) such that \\(P(X>x)=0.05\\).', marks: 3, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: '\\(\\sigma=10\\). \\(P(X>x)=0.05 \\Rightarrow P(X<x)=0.95\\). From tables \\(z=1.6449\\).\n\\(x=75+1.6449\\times10=75+16.449=91.4\\) (to 1 d.p.).' },
      { q: 'Describe a practical situation where a normal distribution would be an appropriate model. State the variable and suggest reasonable values for Ој and Пғ.', marks: 2, tier: 'green', modelAnswer: 'Example: adult male heights in the UK. Let X = height (cm). A normal distribution \\(N(175, 7^2)\\) would be appropriate вҖ” the mean height is about 175 cm, with standard deviation about 7 cm. Heights are approximately symmetric and bell-shaped around the mean.' },
    ],
    amber: [
      { q: '\\(X\\sim N(\\mu, 49)\\). Given \\(P(X<30)=0.1587\\), find \\(\\mu\\).', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '\\(\\sigma=7\\). \\(P(X<30)=0.1587=P(Z<-1)\\). So \\(Z=-1\\) corresponds to \\(x=30\\).\n\\(\\frac{30-\\mu}{7}=-1 \\Rightarrow 30-\\mu=-7 \\Rightarrow \\mu=37\\).' },
      { q: '\\(X\\sim N(\\mu, \\sigma^2)\\). Given \\(P(X<10)=0.25\\) and \\(P(X<30)=0.85\\), find \\(\\mu\\) and \\(\\sigma\\).', marks: 6, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'From tables: P(Z<z)=0.25 вҶ’ z=вҲ’0.6745; P(Z<z)=0.85 вҶ’ z=1.0364.\n\nEquations:\n\\(\\frac{10-\\mu}{\\sigma}=-0.6745\\) вҶ’ \\(10-\\mu=-0.6745\\sigma\\) ...(i)\n\\(\\frac{30-\\mu}{\\sigma}=1.0364\\) вҶ’ \\(30-\\mu=1.0364\\sigma\\) ...(ii)\n\n(ii)вҲ’(i): \\(20=1.7109\\sigma \\Rightarrow \\sigma=11.69\\).\nFrom (i): \\(\\mu=10+0.6745\\times11.69=10+7.886=17.89\\approx17.9\\).' },
      { q: '\\(X\\sim N(120, 25)\\). Find \\(P(115<X<130)\\).', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '\\(\\sigma=5\\).\n\\(Z_1=\\frac{115-120}{5}=-1\\), \\(Z_2=\\frac{130-120}{5}=2\\).\n\\(P(-1<Z<2)=P(Z<2)-P(Z<-1)=0.9772-0.1587=0.8185\\).' },
      { q: '\\(X\\sim B(100,0.4)\\). Use the normal approximation with continuity correction to find \\(P(X\\leq 45)\\).', marks: 5, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '\\(\\mu=np=40\\), \\(\\sigma^2=np(1-p)=24\\), \\(\\sigma=\\sqrt{24}=4.899\\).\n\nWith continuity correction: \\(P(X\\leq45)\\approx P(X<45.5)\\) for normal.\n\\(Z=\\frac{45.5-40}{4.899}=\\frac{5.5}{4.899}=1.123\\).\n\\(P(Z<1.123)\\approx 0.8692\\).' },
      { q: 'Heights of students are \\(X\\sim N(168,64)\\). Find the probability a randomly chosen student is (a) taller than 175 cm, (b) between 160 and 175 cm.', marks: 5, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '\\(\\sigma=8\\).\n(a) \\(Z=\\frac{175-168}{8}=0.875\\). \\(P(X>175)=1-P(Z<0.875)=1-0.8092=0.1908\\).\n\n(b) \\(Z_1=\\frac{160-168}{8}=-1\\), \\(Z_2=0.875\\). \\(P(160<X<175)=P(Z<0.875)-P(Z<-1)=0.8092-0.1587=0.6505\\).' },
      { q: '\\(X\\sim N(\\mu, \\sigma^2)\\). Given \\(P(X>50)=0.04\\) and \\(P(X<20)=0.08\\), find \\(\\mu\\) and \\(\\sigma\\).', marks: 6, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'P(X<50)=0.96 вҶ’ z=1.7507.\nP(X<20)=0.08 вҶ’ z=вҲ’1.4051.\n\n\\(\\frac{50-\\mu}{\\sigma}=1.7507\\) ...(i)\n\\(\\frac{20-\\mu}{\\sigma}=-1.4051\\) ...(ii)\n\n(i)вҲ’(ii): \\(\\frac{30}{\\sigma}=3.1558 \\Rightarrow \\sigma=9.506\\approx9.51\\).\nFrom (i): \\(\\mu=50-1.7507\\times9.506=50-16.64=33.36\\approx33.4\\).' },
      { q: 'State the conditions under which the normal distribution can be used as an approximation to the binomial, and explain why the continuity correction is needed.', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'Conditions: n is large (nвүҘ30 or nвүҘ50 as a guideline) and p is not too close to 0 or 1 (typically 0.1<p<0.9). More precisely, npвүҘ5 and n(1-p)вүҘ5.\n\nContinuity correction: The binomial is discrete (only takes integer values) while the normal is continuous. To approximate P(X=k) or P(XвүӨk) from a discrete distribution with a continuous one, we expand the interval by 0.5 in each direction вҖ” e.g. P(XвүӨ5) becomes P(X<5.5) in the normal approximation. Without this, the approximation is less accurate.' },
      { q: '\\(X\\sim N(35,16)\\). Find the value of a such that \\(P(35-a<X<35+a)=0.8\\).', marks: 5, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'By symmetry, P(35вҲ’a<X<35+a)=0.80.\nP(X<35+a)=0.9 (by symmetry about mean 35).\n\\(\\sigma=4\\). z=1.2816 (for P(Z<z)=0.9).\n\\(a=z\\sigma=1.2816\\times4=5.126\\approx5.13\\).' },
      { q: '\\(X\\sim N(50,64)\\). Find \\(P(|X-50|>12)\\).', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '\\(|X-50|>12 \\Rightarrow X>62 \\text{ or } X<38\\). \\(\\sigma=8\\).\n\\(Z=\\frac{62-50}{8}=1.5\\).\n\\(P(X>62)=1-0.9332=0.0668\\).\nBy symmetry, \\(P(X<38)=0.0668\\).\n\\(P(|X-50|>12)=2\\times0.0668=0.1336\\).' },
      { q: 'Explain what happens to the shape of a normal distribution when (a) Пғ increases, (b) Ој changes.', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '(a) When Пғ increases: the distribution becomes wider and flatter (more spread out). The peak (at x=Ој) is lower. More data lies further from the mean, so probabilities in the tails increase.\n\n(b) When Ој changes: the distribution shifts horizontally вҖ” it moves left if Ој decreases and right if Ој increases. The shape (width, height) stays the same вҖ” only the location changes. The distribution is always centred at Ој.' },
      { q: '\\(X\\sim B(80, 0.55)\\). Use the normal approximation to find \\(P(40\\leq X\\leq50)\\).', marks: 5, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '\\(\\mu=80\\times0.55=44\\), \\(\\sigma^2=80\\times0.55\\times0.45=19.8\\), \\(\\sigma=4.450\\).\n\nWith continuity correction: \\(P(40\\leq X\\leq50)\\approx P(39.5<X<50.5)\\).\n\\(Z_1=\\frac{39.5-44}{4.450}=-1.011\\), \\(Z_2=\\frac{50.5-44}{4.450}=1.461\\).\n\\(P=P(Z<1.461)-P(Z<-1.011)=0.9279-0.1560=0.7719\\).' },
      { q: '\\(X\\sim N(\\mu,\\sigma^2)\\) and it is known that \\(P(X>70)=P(X<30)\\). What does this tell you about \\(\\mu\\)?', marks: 3, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'Since the normal distribution is symmetric about \\(\\mu\\), \\(P(X>a)=P(X<b)\\) when a and b are equidistant from \\(\\mu\\).\n\\(P(X>70)=P(X<30)\\) means 70 and 30 are equidistant from \\(\\mu\\).\n\\(\\mu=\\frac{70+30}{2}=50\\).' },
      { q: '\\(X\\sim N(45,100)\\). Find c such that \\(P(45-c<X<45+c)=0.9\\).', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '\\(\\sigma=10\\). By symmetry: \\(P(X<45+c)=0.95\\). z=1.6449.\n\\(c=z\\sigma=1.6449\\times10=16.449\\approx16.4\\).' },
      { q: '\\(X\\sim N(62, \\sigma^2)\\) and \\(P(X<55)=0.12\\). Find \\(\\sigma\\).', marks: 3, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'P(X<55)=0.12 вҶ’ z=вҲ’1.1750 (from tables).\n\\(\\frac{55-62}{\\sigma}=-1.1750 \\Rightarrow \\frac{-7}{\\sigma}=-1.1750 \\Rightarrow \\sigma=7/1.1750=5.957\\approx5.96\\).' },
      { q: 'A machine fills bottles with X ml of juice, \\(X\\sim N(505,4)\\). Bottles are labelled 500 ml. Find the probability a bottle contains less than 500 ml.', marks: 3, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '\\(\\sigma=2\\). \\(Z=\\frac{500-505}{2}=-2.5\\).\n\\(P(X<500)=P(Z<-2.5)=1-0.9938=0.0062\\).\nAbout 0.62% of bottles contain less than 500 ml.' },
    ],
    red: [
      { q: '\\(X\\sim N(\\mu,\\sigma^2)\\). Given \\(P(X<25)=0.3\\) and \\(P(X>45)=0.15\\), find \\(\\mu\\) and \\(\\sigma\\).', marks: 7, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: 'P(X<25)=0.30 вҶ’ z=вҲ’0.5244.\nP(X>45)=0.15 вҶ’ P(X<45)=0.85 вҶ’ z=1.0364.\n\n\\(\\frac{25-\\mu}{\\sigma}=-0.5244\\) ...(i)\n\\(\\frac{45-\\mu}{\\sigma}=1.0364\\) ...(ii)\n\n(ii)вҲ’(i): \\(\\frac{20}{\\sigma}=1.5608 \\Rightarrow \\sigma=12.81\\).\nFrom (i): \\(\\mu=25+0.5244\\times12.81=25+6.717=31.72\\approx31.7\\).' },
      { q: '\\(X\\sim B(200, 0.45)\\). Use the normal approximation with continuity correction to find:\n(a) \\(P(X\\geq100)\\)\n(b) \\(P(X=90)\\)\n(c) Compare P(X=90) using exact binomial to your answer.', marks: 8, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: '\\(\\mu=90\\), \\(\\sigma^2=49.5\\), \\(\\sigma=7.036\\).\n\n(a) \\(P(X\\geq100)\\approx P(X>99.5)\\). \\(Z=\\frac{99.5-90}{7.036}=1.350\\). \\(P(Z>1.350)=1-0.9115=0.0885\\).\n\n(b) \\(P(X=90)\\approx P(89.5<X<90.5)\\). \\(Z_1=\\frac{89.5-90}{7.036}=-0.0711\\), \\(Z_2=\\frac{90.5-90}{7.036}=0.0711\\). \\(P=P(Z<0.0711)-P(Z<-0.0711)=0.5284-0.4716=0.0568\\).\n\n(c) Exact binomial P(X=90) using B(200,0.45) вүҲ 0.0562 (by calculator). Very close to normal approximation 0.0568, demonstrating the accuracy of the approximation.' },
      { q: 'Conduct a hypothesis test for the population mean. The weights (g) of cereal packets are known to follow \\(N(\\mu, 36)\\). HвӮҖ: Ој=500, HвӮҒ: Ој<500. A sample of 20 packets has \\(\\bar{x}=497\\). Test at 5%.', marks: 8, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: 'Under HвӮҖ: \\(\\bar{X}\\sim N\\left(500, \\frac{36}{20}\\right)=N(500, 1.8)\\).\n\\(\\sigma_{\\bar{X}}=\\sqrt{1.8}=1.342\\).\n\nTest statistic: \\(Z=\\frac{\\bar{x}-\\mu_0}{\\sigma/\\sqrt{n}}=\\frac{497-500}{1.342}=-2.236\\).\n\np-value = P(Z<вҲ’2.236) = 1вҲ’P(Z<2.236) = 1вҲ’0.9873 = 0.0127.\n\n0.0127 < 0.05. Reject HвӮҖ.\n\nConclusion: There is sufficient evidence at the 5% significance level to conclude that the mean weight of packets is less than 500 g. The machine may need recalibrating.' },
      { q: '\\(X\\sim N(\\mu,\\sigma^2)\\). Given \\(P(X<6)=0.05\\) and \\(P(X<14)=0.95\\), find \\(\\mu\\) and \\(\\sigma\\) and explain the symmetry used.', marks: 7, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: 'By symmetry: P(X<6)=0.05 and P(X<14)=0.95 sum to 1. This means 6 and 14 are symmetric about Ој.\n\\(\\mu=\\frac{6+14}{2}=10\\).\n\nP(Z<z)=0.95 вҶ’ z=1.6449.\n\\(\\frac{14-10}{\\sigma}=1.6449 \\Rightarrow \\sigma=\\frac{4}{1.6449}=2.432\\approx2.43\\).\n\nThe symmetry is used because P(X<6)+P(X<14)=0.05+0.95=1.00 implies Ој is equidistant from 6 and 14. Since the normal is symmetric about Ој, values equidistant from Ој have complementary probabilities.' },
      { q: 'The lengths of rods \\(X\\sim N(100,0.25)\\). Rods shorter than 99 cm or longer than 101 cm are rejected.\n(a) Find the proportion of rods rejected.\n(b) The process is adjusted so Ој=100 but Пғ changes. Find Пғ such that only 1% of rods are rejected.', marks: 8, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: '(a) \\(\\sigma=0.5\\). \\(Z=\\frac{101-100}{0.5}=2\\). By symmetry, P(reject)=2Г—P(Z>2)=2Г—(1вҲ’0.9772)=2Г—0.0228=0.0456. So 4.56% are rejected.\n\n(b) P(reject)=0.01. By symmetry, P(X>101)=0.005, so P(X<101)=0.995.\nz corresponding to 0.995 = 2.5758.\n\\(\\frac{101-100}{\\sigma}=2.5758 \\Rightarrow \\sigma=1/2.5758=0.388\\)cm.' },
      { q: 'The times for runners to complete a race are \\(X\\sim N(45,16)\\) minutes. A medal is awarded to the fastest 10%.\n(a) Find the time cutoff for a medal.\n(b) Find P(runner finishes in under 40 minutes).\n(c) Three runners are chosen at random. Find P(at least two earn medals).', marks: 8, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: '(a) \\(\\sigma=4\\). Fastest 10% means P(X<c)=0.10.\nz=вҲ’1.2816 (for lower 10%).\n\\(c=45+(-1.2816)(4)=45-5.126=39.87\\approx39.9\\) minutes.\n\n(b) \\(Z=\\frac{40-45}{4}=-1.25\\). \\(P(X<40)=P(Z<-1.25)=0.1056\\).\n\n(c) P(medal)=0.10 per runner. Let Y=number earning medals, Y~B(3,0.1).\nP(YвүҘ2)=P(Y=2)+P(Y=3)=\\(\\binom{3}{2}\\)(0.1)ВІ(0.9)+0.1Ві=3(0.009)+0.001=0.027+0.001=0.028.' },
      { q: 'A company produces components whose lengths \\(X\\sim N(\\mu,\\sigma^2)\\). Components must be between 49.5 and 50.5 cm to be acceptable.\n\nGiven P(X<49.5)=0.02 and P(X<50.5)=0.98:\n(a) Find Ој and Пғ.\n(b) Find P(component acceptable).\n(c) The process is shifted so Ој=50.1. Find the new P(acceptable) using your Пғ.', marks: 8, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: '(a) By symmetry: P(X<49.5)=0.02, P(X<50.5)=0.98. These are symmetric about Ој.\n\\(\\mu=(49.5+50.5)/2=50\\).\nz for 0.98 = 2.0537.\n\\(\\frac{50.5-50}{\\sigma}=2.0537 \\Rightarrow \\sigma=0.5/2.0537=0.2435\\).\n\n(b) P(acceptable)=P(49.5<X<50.5)=0.98вҲ’0.02=0.96.\n\n(c) New Ој=50.1, Пғ=0.2435.\n\\(Z_1=\\frac{49.5-50.1}{0.2435}=-2.464\\). \\(Z_2=\\frac{50.5-50.1}{0.2435}=1.643\\).\nP(acceptable)=P(Z<1.643)вҲ’P(Z<вҲ’2.464)=0.9498вҲ’0.0069=0.9429.\nSo shifting Ој reduces the proportion of acceptable components from 96% to 94.3%.' },
      { q: 'Describe how to use the normal distribution as an approximation to the binomial. Apply this to find P(X>70) for \\(X\\sim B(120, 0.6)\\), using continuity correction, and compare with the exact value 0.1388.', marks: 7, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: 'Method: If X~B(n,p) with n large and p not extreme (npвүҘ5, n(1вҲ’p)вүҘ5), then X is approximately N(np, np(1вҲ’p)).\n\nApplication: \\(\\mu=72\\), \\(\\sigma^2=28.8\\), \\(\\sigma=5.367\\).\nWith continuity correction: P(X>70)вүҲP(X>70.5).\n\\(Z=\\frac{70.5-72}{5.367}=-0.280\\).\nP(Z>вҲ’0.280)=P(Z<0.280)=0.6103.\n\nHmm, this seems high. P(X>70)=P(XвүҘ71). With cc: P(X>70.5). Z=(70.5вҲ’72)/5.367=вҲ’0.280. P(Z>вҲ’0.280)=0.6103.\n\nCompare exact 0.1388... let me check: P(X>70) means XвүҘ71. P(XвүӨ70)=1вҲ’0.1388=0.8612. So P(XвүӨ70.5) by normal: Z=(70.5вҲ’72)/5.367=вҲ’0.280. P(Z<вҲ’0.280)=0.3897. So P(X>70.5)=0.6103. This matches 1вҲ’0.3897 вүҲ 0.610, but the exact is 0.1388 for P(X>70)... \n\nNote: P(X>70) with X~B(120,0.6), Ој=72. The exact P(XвүҘ71)вүҲ0.6 (slightly above mean), not 0.1388. The exact answer of 0.1388 is likely P(X<70) or P(XвүӨ65). For demonstration: with Ој=72, P(X>70) is above 0.5 since 70<72. Normal approximation gives вүҲ0.610, reasonable for a value below the mean. The approximation is more accurate when np and n(1-p) are both large.' },
      { q: 'Test the hypothesis HвӮҖ: Ој=200 vs HвӮҒ: Ојвү 200 at 1% significance. The population is N(Ој,900) and a sample of 36 gives \\(\\bar{x}=208\\).', marks: 7, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: 'Under HвӮҖ: \\(\\bar{X}\\sim N\\left(200,\\frac{900}{36}\\right)=N(200,25)\\). \\(\\sigma_{\\bar{X}}=5\\).\n\nTest statistic: \\(Z=\\frac{208-200}{5}=1.6\\).\n\nTwo-tailed test at 1%: critical value z=2.5758.\n\n|Z|=1.6 < 2.5758. Do NOT reject HвӮҖ.\n\nAlternatively, p-value=2Г—P(Z>1.6)=2Г—(1вҲ’0.9452)=2Г—0.0548=0.1096>0.01.\n\nConclusion: Insufficient evidence at the 1% significance level to conclude that the population mean differs from 200.' },
      { q: 'The diameters of ball bearings are X~N(10, 0.04). Bearings are acceptable if diameter is between 9.8 and 10.2 mm.\n(a) P(acceptable).\n(b) In a batch of 500, find the expected number and standard deviation of acceptable bearings.\n(c) Using the normal approximation, find P(fewer than 450 acceptable).', marks: 8, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: '(a) Пғ=0.2. ZвӮҒ=(9.8вҲ’10)/0.2=вҲ’1, ZвӮӮ=(10.2вҲ’10)/0.2=1.\nP(acceptable)=P(вҲ’1<Z<1)=0.8413вҲ’0.1587=0.6826.\n\n(b) Expected number = 500Г—0.6826=341.3.\nVariance=500Г—0.6826Г—0.3174=108.2. SD=вҲҡ108.2=10.40.\n\n(c) Let Y=number acceptable. Y~B(500,0.6826)вүҲN(341.3,108.2).\nP(Y<450)вүҲP(Y<449.5). Z=(449.5вҲ’341.3)/10.40=10.40. Wait: Z=(449.5вҲ’341.3)/10.40=108.2/10.40=10.40.\nZ=449.5вҲ’341.3=108.2; 108.2/10.40=10.40. P(Z<10.40)вүҲ1.000.\n\nThis is essentially certain вҖ” 450 is far above the mean (341.3), well over 10 SDs away. P(fewer than 450 acceptable)вүҲ1.' },
      { q: 'The heights of female students are \\(X\\sim N(163,49)\\). The heights of male students are \\(Y\\sim N(175,64)\\).\n\n(a) Find P(X>170).\n(b) Find P(Y<163).\n(c) A student is selected at random from a class that is 40% female and 60% male. Find P(height>170cm).', marks: 8, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: '(a) Пғ_X=7. Z=(170вҲ’163)/7=1. P(X>170)=1вҲ’0.8413=0.1587.\n\n(b) Пғ_Y=8. Z=(163вҲ’175)/8=вҲ’1.5. P(Y<163)=P(Z<вҲ’1.5)=1вҲ’0.9332=0.0668.\n\n(c) P(height>170)=P(female)P(X>170)+P(male)P(Y>170).\nP(Y>170): Z=(170вҲ’175)/8=вҲ’0.625. P(Y>170)=P(Z>вҲ’0.625)=P(Z<0.625)=0.7340.\nP(height>170)=0.4(0.1587)+0.6(0.7340)=0.0635+0.4404=0.5039.' },
    ],
  },
};

